ussed behind closed doors and, above all, lobbying hard. CETA is a treaty negotiated by the European Commission with Canada between 2009 and 2014. After that, some minor adjustments were made to the investment protection mechanism, ICS, under considerable public pressure. In the long term, 98% of import duties will be completely abolished. Canada is a major exporter of agricultural products such as rape, wheat, soya, beef, potatoes and pork. In exchange for the lower import rates of Canadian agriculture, European pharmaceutical companies will have the right to extend their patents in Canada longer. That means profit for Big Pharma in Europe and higher costs for people who need medicine in Canada and elsewhere in the world. Europe can also export more milk and cheese to Canada. Of course, this raises the question of how this relates to the circular vision, which, after the signing of CETA, has been officially designated by this cabinet as the path that farmers must take. How does this relate to the climate targets that this cabinet will have to meet? In doing so, the cabinet cannot look away from the livestock, and therefore not, precisely, from the dairy herd. Mr. Chairman. We have asked several questions about working groups of European and Canadian officials who can adapt everything to the Treaty in backrooms. No clear answer has yet been given to this question. That's a lot to think about. The treaty is, let me say it carefully, controversial. The only line of defense that the persistent supporters are the VVD, the CDA and D66; those are the only three parties that are heartfeltly in favour of his........................................................................................................................................................................................................................................... On balance, they mean, because these proponents also recognise that there are also people who are becoming poorer with CETA and that we will also have climate and nature effects. But yes, so they say, there are always winners and losers. And the losers should just be happy that others are getting rich or something. As long as we get richer as a whole, that's good for everyone. Mr. Chairman. This way of thinking, this cold neoliberal calculus, has caused great havoc in the world. Also in the Netherlands. The idea that if we get richer on balance, then everyone gets better, they're gonna be lied to every day. Look at Ireland; if I am not mistaken in recent years, the country with the highest economic growth in all European Member States. There's more people out there than ever. That's not how it works. You can't say we're getting richer, and so that's good for everyone. Certainly not if the way in which you get richer only goes through the disproportionate advantage of big business, at the expense of citizens' rights, at the expense of the capital that belongs to all of us. Whether you're rich or poor, the natural resources our nature, a healthy climate should be equally accessible to everyone. The cabinet puts that on sale because of a trade deal with Canada. Mr. Chairman. It's this old thought that we need to get rid of very quickly at the beginning of 2020, the new decade. CETA is therefore a convulsion of thinking that has had its longest time. I was pleasantly surprised by the insights that also appeared with the VVD and also with D66 during the past political reflections. There are limits to growth, said group chairman Rob Jetten. That's great fun, but when is D66 gonna respect those boundaries? Liberalism must go back to working for people, said the leader of the VVD. Yeah, it's great! But why do you now agree to a free trade agreement based on that old thinking, which you are asking critical questions about? Minister Kaag says it would be a historic mistake if we did not ratify CETA. I say it is a historic mistake if we approve what should have been in the trash a long time ago today. Because the insights have changed and the world has changed. Since the European Commission concluded the trade deal with Canada, we signed the Climate Agreement, this cabinet acknowledged that the current agricultural system is unsustainable, it pointed out the circular agriculture as an official new course that Dutch farmers should follow and presented Minister Schouten with a vision of the future of poison use that means \"we use far too much poison in Dutch agriculture; that really has to go down.\" Since the negotiation of CETA, the nitrogen crisis also broke out, which various parties here have said about, and I am glad to say that agriculture must really change. It has to be, but then you can't make it to open the door at the border to tough competition. Since CETA's negotiation, the European Commission has presented a green deal with a lot of bombs. And the European Parliament adopted a resolution saying that animal welfare in the European Union should go to a higher level. If you want to do all that, you can't go on with CETA. Or you're and will remain a two-faced administration that the citizens and the farmers can't count on. Let me give you a few examples of agriculture. Thank you to Mr Diks, who has already explained a lot of things that we regret to have to repair here today, because the minister in the newspapers and on television has turned his eyes on all the opponents. The facts are: yes, the products exported from Canada to Europe must meet product standards at the border, such as the same food safety requirements and animal health requirements. That is quite different from production requirements. I'm just going to refer the minister back to her waving the Bible. Does she think it's fair to tell half the story, the story that sounds good and makes people think there's nothing wrong? In Canada, farmers have to do the same thing as in Europe, so why bother with abolishing these import tariffs? Well, because the minister deliberately tells half a story. She was even throwing sand in her opponent's eyes so badly that the advocates didn't understand it anymore. I saw Mr Weverling say at Radar that Canadian farmers must meet the same animal welfare requirements as those in Europe. That's just not true. What the Minister always means is that if the meat is on the European border, it may contain as little salmonella as it does in Europe. It does not say that the rules on animal welfare in Canada are much lower than in the European Union. She's not very honest, is she? Mr. Chairman. For example, Canadian farmers may also use poisons that are no longer allowed here. We have had to fight long and hard for that. That fight is far from over. Neonics, those super-dangerous toxins that have been classified as very disastrous for insects, for bees, have finally been restricted in open crops in the Netherlands after a long time. In Canada, farmers can still use them. What does the Minister say to farmers who don't think that's fair? They must compete against farmers who are allowed to use toxins and thus produce cheaper and more mass than they do. The Minister simply doesn't answer that. What's that about? Group accommodation for sows is not mandatory in Canada. The minister says Canada's working on it. In 2014, the Convention was negotiated between the European Commission and Canada. They've had six years. We haven't seen anything yet. So what do you mean, they're working on it? The hard facts in that treaty say that the European market is open to Canadian pork. The soft side is that we're going to talk to Canada a little bit if they want to change their rules too. You have no guarantee of that. Experience has shown that this is not going to happen either. Canada has not yet shown that they are serious, because otherwise they would have done it in six years. The hard facts are about to compete with European farmers and the soft, anointing words that the Minister speaks mean nothing at all. It is dramatic for the animals and it is unfair to the farmers. The funny thing is, the cabinet gets it, too. I read a quote: \"When I hear some politicians, they really want to compete on these kinds of rules. But if a cheap pesticide is allowed in a particular country, but because it is not bad for the environment in the EU, then you don't want the products used to come on the market with us.\" It was Minister Blok who said this, in the context of the negotiations with the United Kingdom, now that the Brexit has continued. So when it comes to the United Kingdom, the Cabinet understands that you do not do that to bully the British, but simply because it is not fair to your own farmers. So if you understand that for the United Kingdom, why wouldn't you understand that for Canada? Mr. Chairman. If you ask the farmers, they say \"no.\" What really surprises the Animal Party is that the coalition parties seem to be okay with Minister Schouten meeting the farmers in everything, but Minister Kaag in absolutely nothing. She doesn't have to do that at all. However, if you declare the current agricultural system untenable, then the trade policy that has driven this system is of course quite the same thing. Farmers do not go on their own for just bigger, just more, competing at cost and bulk production. Doesn't make anyone happy. Because it had to be in this cold commercial policy of this cabinet, and there was no protection whatsoever, agriculture has developed so that we now say that the whole system is unsustainable. Then you have to start by looking at the driver of it. It's cause and effect. Our blind trade drive, our neoliberal trade policy, has been the driving force behind an agricultural system in which we have to stop five to seven farmers a day, because they cannot win the unequal battle, and that everyone who knows about it has seen it as untenable for at least twenty years. It is recognized by the cabinet, but it is a cabinet with two faces. It wants to reform agriculture, but not shut down the driver of the bankrupt agricultural model. Then there is the exclusive investment protection for multinationals. Only multinationals, foreign investors with activities in Canada can challenge the Dutch State and other EU Member States to a separate investment tribunal. Trade unions, citizens, environmental organisations and states themselves cannot do that. Soon no one seems to want this tribunal anymore. The minister says I didn't have to. The VVD says: neither do we, but yes, there were others who wanted to, so why not? But why not listen to trade unions, consumer organisations, food safety watchdogs, privacy clubs, critical Canadian parliamentarians, environmental organisations and many others? They all say, \"Don't do it.\" Why don't we listen to them? The Vermillions, the ExxonMobils, the Halliburtons and the Cargills of this world, who already enjoy enough protection and have barracks with lawyers to make the most of any possibility offered by national legal systems to protect their own interests, receive additional investment protection, because they do feel that the enormous climate transition could be at the expense of their fossil investments. Why give these companies even more power over the legal system, which in itself takes into account the risk of expropriation when a state takes a decision at the expense of investment? That protection is already there. Then why is it so necessary to give these multinationals an extra layer of protection?"}, {"speech id": "ParlaMint-NL_2020-02-12-tweedekamer-7.u361", "speech text": "Yeah, but if D66's gonna set up these lines of defense, it's gonna have to be countered with the facts. The conversations we've seen..."}, {"speech id": "ParlaMint-NL_2020-02-12-tweedekamer-7.u404", "speech text": "Now the monkey's coming out of the sleeve. Chinese, Brazilians: creating scare images, that was also the CDA's defense at the dividend tax. While they knew that dividend tax was for the three big multinationals, they came up with stories