ain people and keep the rest of society open. I feel supported by thousands of doctors at home and abroad who have sounded the alarm clock and plead for a radically different policy. Tomorrow I will discuss this extensively in the Corona debate. That is why I am now moving on to the following threat to our prosperity: the absurd climate plans. This horse of the Apocalypse, this second horse, is ridden by jockey Frans Timmermans, European champion, with his stablehandler Diederik Samsom, head of Timmermans' cabinet and responsible for implementing the Green Deal. These are thousands of billions wasted on inefficient wind turbines and solar panels. They do not want to call it \"costs\"; they would be \"investments.\" So your home isolation would be recouped in about 250 years. \"Creative accounting,\" we call it. Mr. Chairman. As long as nuclear energy is excluded for ideological reasons, we are threatening to commit a historic failure of unprecedented proportions. Nuclear energy is clean and cheap and ensures that citizens and businesses no longer have to suffer under expensive and compelling climate requirements. Last week, we were pleased to see that nuclear energy is the future. This will undoubtedly last until March 17, 2021, but unfortunately experience has shown that the VVD election promises after elections are often forgotten again. Nevertheless, a glimmer of hope. But then there's mass immigration. Apart from the disastrous effects it has on culture, it is also a disaster for the economy. So the third horse from the Apocalypse. For why is there never a proper debate on the economic damage caused by mass immigration? We often hear debates about culture, but not often about the economy, which is therefore deeply disrupted. Why not make a thorough analysis of the costs and benefits of the open immigration lock that the Netherlands has become under the Rutte Cabinets over the last ten years? No less than 750,000 people have joined the Netherlands since 2010, often illegal as well. It seems extremely useful to calculate on balance what immigrants have contributed to the Dutch economy after deduction of costs such as housing, benefits, medical care and social side effects. Elsevier calculated a few years ago that the cost of immigration has already risen to 200 billion. These are about the benefits of the Dutch natural gas fields since 1970. We could have been swimming in the money if we had spent those billions better. We could have invested in care, education, defense, housing and security. What a dream country the Netherlands could have been. Unfortunately, the cartel parties have decided to change their policies. VVD, CDA and the other parties that have been in power for the past 40 years have not chosen to do so. We cannot go back, but for the coming years it is possible to change the policy substantially. In any case, we are in favour of stopping all immigration which does not concern people who are going to make a positive contribution to our national economy. We only want people to come to the Netherlands to bring something. Every year the population of our country grows with about 100,000 people. That's about the size of a city like Delft, every year. It can and must not continue like this. Unfortunately, for decades, the government parties have been deaf and blind to the question of how many people can actually live in the Netherlands without the care, housing and our social services succumb because too many people rely on it without contributing to the carrying capacity. And finally, the fourth horse: the geopolitical project to integrate all the national states in Europe into a bureaucratic monster state, the European Union. We can be blind, as the prisoners in the cave that Plato described, or we can simply admit that the economic consequences of a transfer union have been hidden from the citizens. We are completely deceived with orwellian newspeak, in which donations in a bottomless pit are praised as loans, wh