 standard for safe distance in these emergency laws gives room and a legal basis for this. The same applies to measures that determine how much visit you may receive at home. They are now given a legal basis. This narrows and grinds down the house law contained in the Constitution. That brings me to democratic control. At the heart of our constitutional system is the fact that the Parliament takes part in the content of, participates in and participates in the decision on essential freedom measures through legal rules; on restrictions on our fundamental fundamental rights. So freedom can't be restricted without the consent of parliament. You can't just leave that to the Minister. It concerns far-reaching powers, which affect us all, in the hands of unelected ministers and unelected mayors. I do not see an adequate ID for that at the moment. Because with the version of the emergency law, like the one without amendments, which I would like to stress once again, the Minister of Health is given the power to impose measures on the population, for example on group formation and keeping away from them, by means of so-called ministerial regulations. The Lower House can then discuss this measure and submit motions, after which the Minister is asked to amend the measure or to abandon it altogether. But the minister, the cabinet, can ignore that. So even if the House of Representatives does not agree with the Minister's measures, these measures can continue. In addition, of course, we also have a coalition force, so that questionable measures can always count on striking votes. By the way, the cabinet can always ignore motions that have been adopted and, whether disguised or not, it can be said that it is impossible for all kinds of blurry reasons or that it is extremely difficult to respond to what the motion asks. Every Member of Parliament does have such a tray of adopted motions and commitments that can be called, e-mailed and recalled in any subsequent debate. But do it? 