 terms and restrictions of freedom, which are then, and then again are not, ratified by the Chamber. Can the Minister clearly and clearly define what is directly and indirectly at risk in relation to the measures which he can take under the provisions of this emergency law? We'd better get that straightaway. Speaking of clarity, I refer to Articles 58d and 58e, on the powers of the chairman of the security region and the differentiation and derogations. An amendment from the CDA has already been tabled to that effect. That is what I would like to say briefly about the extension of democratic control over the exercise of powers transferred to the President of the security region. I wholeheartedly support that. But last week there were more criticisms and concerns about these two articles in the Emergency Act, by the VNG, the Aldermen's Association, the Security Council and the Dutch Society of Mayors. They clearly have concerns about local customization, which is made conditional on the Minister's decision to give this power to the mayor. There are concerns about the coordination, enforcement and implementation of the measures. There are concerns about confusion in society about its lack. About the coordinating role of the President of the security region, which seems to be insufficiently anchored. On democratic legitimacy at local level, which is not sufficiently guaranteed. On the maintenance of safe distance and on the formation of groups in the case of students. Finally, there are questions about the interpretation of the autonomous administrative power of municipalities, namely what scope is actually left for that under this emergency law. Mr. Chairman. It is hard for ordinary people to follow, but now that it is also inimitable at this level of security regions and municipalities, I would like to ask the Minister to write a manual specifically for Articles 58d and 58e, a clear roadmap, on what should be done on a decentralised basis with this regulation. I have also spoken to a state law professor about this. He also says that the risk is being taken here, which is in fact inevitable that the layers of government are going to collide. The direction is incredibly clumsy. Can the Minister, therefore, put together a manual with great urgency, but of course with great care? Mr. Chairman. Finally, on Article 58 (1) (a), I would like to say why there is a further piece of age discrimination in this area. What the hell is that for? How far does that go? It goes against Article 1 of the Constitution. I'm also looking at 50PLUS with a oblique eye. Perhaps we could work together to put together another amendment to get that age discrimination out of that article of the law. On the interim article 58g about group formation I will come back to the end. I hear Mrs. Kuik say \"58a.\" Excuse me? I'm on it, Mr. Chairman. On Article 58g, on group formation, I will come back to the end. Article 58o. I welcome the 50PLUS amendment which regulates that nursing homes are no longer in overall lockdown where residents can no longer see any loved or caregiver. I very much support that. On Article 58p concerning passenger transport, I have a specific question for the Minister. Is my lecture that paragraph 2 provides the opportunity to deviate from the fact that people from one household can sit together in a car? I find that rather complicated: exception to exception. The outside guard, the people at home, doesn't understand anything about this. Can the Minister explain clearly in what specific situations he wishes to make use of this possibility and what this will help in the fight against the virus? That's not gonna make it any easier. Shouldn't that exception just come out all the way? I would be happy to table an amendment on that today. Mr. Chairman. I come to Rule 58t, on accountability and information. Paragraph 1 states: \"Our Minister shall send monthly to both Chambers of the States General a reasoned statement of the measures in force 