 going on with these regulations to remove the notes. And does the Minister also intend to reduce the already imposed \u20ac390 corona fines to the amount of \u20ac95, as will be regulated by law for future corona fines? Mr. Chairman. In particular, in the first months of the corona crisis, approximately 17,000 criminal orders were issued for a violation of a rule in the covide emergency regulations, such as the fine for the violation of the safe distance standard or the one and a half meter measure, and a violation of the ban on group formation that is closely related to this. In the meantime, 6.872 oppositions have been made against these corona fines. Before that, in the last few days, the first people were in court. The day before yesterday 22 people fought their corona fine at the canton court in Arnhem. By far the majority of people are not assisted in their corona case by an attorney. They therefore stand without a lawyer, alone in court, leaving legal defenses undisputed. I'm very sorry about that. The most up-to-date political situation, such as no criminal record and possibly a lower fine, was also discussed at the hearing. What does the Minister of Justice and Security think about most people without lawyers being brought to justice? People who, due to a corona fine, have to appear before the canton court do not, in principle, receive compensation for a lawyer because it is a motto: for the canton court you have to be able to defend yourself. This is often about traffic fines and other minor penalties. But these corona fines are basic discussions, discussions about whether an emergency regulation has been able to serve as a basis for restricting fundamental rights. That's what we're talking about in the Chamber today, and that's why we're dealing with this emergency bill. Anyone who wishes to take a lawyer to the canton court after a criminal offence and cannot afford to do so can in principle ask the Legal Aid Council to make an exception. But hardly any