riate to combat the epidemic can be imposed by the Minister. Mr. Chairman. The text of Article 58b has been incorporated into the law on the basis of an amendment accepted unanimously. I read in the second paragraph that powers are only applied if they are necessary in view of the seriousness of the threat to public health. It clearly says \"is necessary\" and not \"if the Minister considers that measure appropriate.\" Both the judiciary and science agree that the three basic requirements of necessity, proportionality and subsidiarity also lay down the requirement of suitability. I quote Professor Janneke Gerards from her contribution to the collection The principle of proportionality of art. 3:4 Awb and European law: \"To be able to speak of a proportionate decision, this decision must first of all be an effective means of achieving the objectives pursued by the decision. The requirement of fitness.\" I read here that the decision must first of all be an effective means. This means that if scientists find that a measure is not established that it effectively contributes to the fight against the epidemic, it must not be taken. It would then be contrary to Article 58b, second paragraph. But according to the answer to my previous written question, the Minister sees it differently. If the Minister already states that he explains Article 58b (2) in such a way that he reserves the right to take a measure that is not scientifically considered effective, then we have a problem. He then nibbles off the sharpness of the legislative text and brings everything back into his own sphere of competence, which was not the intention of the authors of the amendment. Our group wishes to make this clear. It concludes from Article 58b that freedom-limiting measures should only be applied if generally accepted scientific standards are sufficiently established that those measures will be effective. Is that right? I'd like a response from the Minister. The Minister agrees with us that consideration should be given not only to the importance of the threat to public health, but also to the importance of preventing unemployment, loneliness, damage to the living environment, learning disadvantages, greater inequality of opportunity and other general interests. However, those who read the text of Article 58b do not find this balancing framework. The text merely highlights the importance of combating the epidemic. This interest is, in principle, a priority, although the proportionality test may prevent conflicting interests from doing so. These conflicting interests are the interests of the citizens who are affected and to whom fundamental rights belong. We have received thousands of very concerned e-mails and letters from those citizens. If the exercise of the fundamental rights of those citizens is restricted, the second paragraph (c) of Article 58b states that that restriction must comply with the requirements of proportionality and subsidiarity. Thus, if the number of people allowed to come together is limited, churchgoers may hinder in their freedom of religion Article 6 of the Constitution.................................................................................................................................................... Or it may hinder demonstrators in their freedom of assembly and demonstration (Article 7 of the Constitution). The introduction of the one-and-a-half-metre society could generally restrict citizens' right to privacy, as provided for in Article 8 of the Constitution. That limitation must not be disproportionate at all times. Article 58b, second paragraph (c), deals only with the limitation of the exercise of such fundamental rights by citizens. The legal framework does not include the need to assess the importance of combating the epidemic in conjunction with other general interests which should also be addressed by the public authorities. According to the second paragraph of Article 58b (c), it is only a possible disproportionate restriction on the exercise of fundamental rights by citizens. That review framework does not require the inclusion of objectives other than the objective of combating the epidemic, such as the objective of promoting adequate employment, protection and improvement of the environment, social and cultural development and adequate and sound education, etc. Mr. Chairman. The one-dimensional character of the law is easy to illustrate. Take the requirement of 1.5 meters away and the maximum number of persons of 30 who may be present in a theatre hall. The 1.5 meter distance limits the citizen-theatre visitor in his fundamental right. Review under the conditions laid down in Article 58 (2) (c) may lead to the result that that restriction complies with the proportionality requirement. Then the trade-off is done, and rightfully. The fact that only 30 people are allowed to sit in the theatre does not affect any of the citizens' fundamental rights. Therefore, the proportionality assessment required in Article 58b (2) (c) does not relate to this. The adverse effect of the measure on the general interest of cultural development will not be taken into account in the consideration required under Article 58b. Or take students and students who are no longer able to attend physical education. If this leads to disadvantage in learning and to deterioration in the quality of education, it is not a violation of a fundamental right to which Article 58b (2) (c) refers. A disproportionate balance of interests cannot then be demonstrated. Mr. Chairman. The aim of combating the epidemic and reducing the threat to public health is the law's sole objective, whereas it is precisely to what extent that objective is justified in relation to other objectives which the public authorities should pursue in the public interest. The legal formulation used in the design creates a tunnel where other societal goals are excluded. As a result, there is no legal obligation to consider these other objectives as equivalent in principle. Mr. Chairman. In the wake of the first sudden corona wave, it was understandable that at that time the government could only think of one goal: protection of public health in a narrow sense. In the meantime, however, it is clear that such a one-dimensional tunnel legislation is not adequate and that it also increasingly encounters social resistance. In the NRC of 9 October, even the directors of the Central Planning Bureau, the Planning Office for the Environment and the Social and Cultural Planning Office called on the government to focus on more than just slowing down the corona virus and reducing direct economic damage during the corona crisis. That broader balancing framework should be laid down in this law. Mr. Chairman. One question. Does the Group of the Party of Animals think it right that Article 58b, second paragraph (c) refers exclusively to the balance of interests in relation to measures which restrict the exercise of fundamental rights by citizens? Isn't that what it says? We would like to know how the Minister sees it. And the following question: does the Minister agree with the Group of the Party of Animals that the legal framework in Article 58b is therefore too limited? Mr. Chairman. I promised to talk about self-mutilation. That's about this house. The law grants virtually blank powers to ministers who are given the power to take decisive action. In order to ensure democratic control, provisions are included which provide that what ministers wish to regulate must be submitted in advance to both chambers of the States General. The democratic accountability applies both to the Lower House and to the Upper Chamber. A government or minister is dependent on the trust of both chambers, with which it is established that, in terms of the functioning of democracy, both chambers occupy an equal place. In technical terms, there is a difference that the First Chamber does not have the right of initiative and amendment, but that does not prejudice the principle that both Chambers have an equivalent position as regards democratic accountability. Now, by agreeing to this bill, the First Chamber should accept that the democratic control introduced by the amendment in the law as a guarantee against the creation of violations of fundamental rights to be determined by ministers alone would be the sole responsibility of the House of Representatives. We in this House are therefore about to have our own power to prevent ministers from acting alone, cutting off our position of democratic control. That has never been shown in parliamentary history and we should never agree to it, as far as the Animal Party is concerned. It is not imaginable, but it is evident that other groups in the First Chamber would agree to such self-mutilation. The information provided by the Council of State does not make this any different, quite the contrary. On the contrary, it strengthens the conviction that the right granted to the Lower House in Article 58c (2) and (3) must also be granted to the Upper Chamber. The Council of State had been asked to examine the arrangements laid down in the amendment \"from a legal and state point of view.\" He concluded that the regime was not contrary to the Constitution and that the legal figure chosen by law had been used before. The Council of State should have left it at that. However, he spoke unsolicited about the question of whether it is justifiable that only the Second Chamber should have the right of assent. Our group considers this to be very inappropriate. The conclusion of the Council of State is then incomprehensible. He pointed out that the First Chamber had no right of initiative and amendment, and that, I quote, 'incoming legislative proposals can only be adopted in full or rejected'. \"In that light,\" the quote continues, \"and in view of the speed of action to be taken,\" the Council of State then considers it \"defendable\" to restrict the First Chamber in its democratic control power. But, Mr President, if the ministerial regulation is offered in accordance with the bill, then the House of Representatives can only say yes or no. Then it is absolutely irrelevant whether the Court has the right of initiative and amendment. And if both chambers have to decide within one week, the same week, what does that do to the speed? If the House of Representatives has a right of assent for a week, then there will not be a week if the House of Representatives has to agree in the same week? The arguments of the Council of State are wrong. And that is not a good thing, especially now that many citizens are suspicious of this law. Mr. Chairman. Our group would like to hear from the Minister whether he agrees with her that if the right of assent is granted to both Chambers within the same week, there will be no unacceptable delay that would not be discussed if only the Lower House had the right to assent. I'd like a response. It can't be that the First Chamber is putting itself out of play when it comes to controlling ministerial arrangements. This creates an unacceptable democratic deficit. Mr. Chairman. I come now to another democratic deficit. I noticed that we are the only ones who have pointed this out. It's not an insignificant matter. On June 16, 2020, the Federation of Medical Specialists and the KNMG adopted a Triage Roadmap. In the final phase of the so-called black scenario, according to the script, \"will be switched to triage according to considerations that lie outside the medical domain.\" But that triage will be carried out by doctors on the basis of non-statutory criteria, which are not medical. Our group has asked whether the Minister agrees with us that criteria for that final stage should be laid down by the government. The answer to our questions on this point does not, in the opinion of our group, give any clarity. On the one hand, the Minister seems to suggest that the definition of criteria outside the medical domain can be left to the profession, but on the other hand the Minister acknowledges that there may be a task for the legislator to clarify that there can be no triage only on the basis of age. We have two questions. If, at any point in time, ic's are full and the triage can no longer take place on the basis of medical considerations, is it not necessary in a democratic rule of law for the legislator to determine who is to be given priority on the basis of transparent and verifiable rules? And shouldn't measures covid-19 provide a basis for this in the Temporary Law? I'd like a clear answer from the Minister. And I'll continue. If that phase enters and there are no triage rules laid down by the government, isn't the expectation that patients' relatives will discuss with doctors who are self-sufficient, on the basis of non-medical considerations, refusing patients on the ic? Shouldn't there even be physical protest in hospitals if the doctors fail to convince the family of the fairness of a decision? I would also like a response from the Minister. Mr President, I come to the end of my speech. I promised I'd talk about evergreens. Minister De Jonge spoke to me about evergreens in the debate in the House of Representatives. That was in the debate with the Group of the Party of Animals. He was referring to the problem of mink. This sector is, by the way, more like a 'nevergreen'. The sector is based purely on money and pride, where defenseless animals are gassed for their fur. An amendment prohibiting the professional breeding of mink due to public health risks had broad support in the House of Representatives, but was eventually not adopted. The Minister also takes the view, when answering our group's questions in the First Chamber, that there is no need for a regulation in this law on that point, because both the Animal Health and Welfare Act and the Public Health Act would include powers that could be used to impose a breeding ban. I studied both laws and I have to conclude that the Minister is wrong. There is no provision in the Public Health Act that provides a basis for banning the keeping of mink or other animals that COVID-19 can transfer. The Animal Health and Welfare Act does not confer powers relating to the public health of humans. Combating the spread of COOVID-19 from animal to human is not a subject regulated by that law. Nor can the ban on breeding which can be imposed under Article 55 of that law be based on the importance of preventing human contamination. Other provisions of that law do not provide a basis for a breeding ban to prevent the spread of COOVID-19 to humans. Does the Minister agree with our group? If so, does he agree with us that a basis for such a breeding ban on animals that are detectable for COVID-19 or any other zoonosis with pandemic threat, which can form a reservoir for that virus and which can transfer that virus to humans, should be included in the Temporary Law measures covid-19? Mr. Chairman. The corona measures currently in force, such as the closure of hotels, the ban on team sports, etc., are based solely on risk avoidance. It is established that mink farms pose a risk for the spread of COOVID-19."}, {"speech id": "ParlaMint-NL_2020-10-27-eerstekamer-11.u8", "speech text": "Mr. Chairman. Ten years of Cabinet Rutte. The last budget of this cabinet and perhaps also the last budget that this Prime Minister has submitted. Corona has turned everything upside down, including the budgetary policy of Rutte I, II and III. In the last year, the savings have been turned around, saving for nine years. Nine years of economy and then in one year the pot is empty again. I'd like to compliment the Prime Minister. Thanks to so much economy in the past, the first blows to the economy were taken and many households were saved a financial death toll. But, to some extent, the cuts have laid the foundations for the problems now. Think about the staff shortages and the capacity problems in hospitals. Corona c