re was a majority in favour. It was a limited right to speak. The victim was only allowed to talk about the impact the crime had had on his life. Even though it was a limited right to speak, it was nevertheless a revolution in criminal law, according to the judges, the Public Prosecutor's Office and the lawyer, because not only the defendant, but also his victim would now be considered as a trial participant at the hearing. Mr. Chairman. We've been 16 years. The legal right to speak has worked out well, meets a need and usually does not disturb the order during the hearing. Over the years, however, it has continued to expand. The victim can now also talk about the burden of proof, the question of proof, the type of punishment and the measure of punishment. In addition, in 2016, the group of spokespersons was expanded. What can it actually be, because the opponents of that time are now defenders of a much wider extension and the advocates of the past voted against this bill. Let me take out two groups. GroenLinks in the Lower House cited Germany's example and said that the victim in the Netherlands should also be able to do a \"Nebenanklage.\" The victim in that German model becomes a surrogate prosecutor who can claim punishment against the defendant. The Minister did not want to go that far, I am happy to say, because that would substantially change our system of criminal proceedings, essentially an indictment by the Public Prosecutor on behalf of society and thus also on behalf of the victim against the defendant. Then the fraction of D66. Sixteen years ago, the House of Representatives was a strong supporter of the extension of victim rights. We felt that the victim should be able to speak for himself about what the defendant might have done to him or her. Why would you leave that to the state's attorney's office or the judge? We thought the victim should do it himself. In those years, we had to overcome a lot of fresh headwinds in order, through initiatives, to strike new picket poles in criminal law and criminal proceedings. Think of the extended application of DNA in criminal law, the right to speak for victims, the lifting of the limitation period in the case of murder, an initiative bill that I, together with Mr Rietkerk of the CDA, brought by the Second and First Chambers and criminalising stalking, of beling. However, in considering this bill in the Lower House, the D66 group as the only group in the Lower House voted against, because the group had reservations about the defendant's obligation to appear, both at the substantive sessions and at the hearing. The group felt that the title of the bill did not really cover the load. The law is called \"Law Enlargement Victim's Rights,\" but the defendant's obligation to appear doesn't have much to do with that, the D66 group found in the Lower House. I'll get back to that in a minute. I believe that Mrs De Boer also said that there are a number of things that are covered in this bill. The first part of the bill anchors the moment of the right to speak at the hearing, namely for the requisition. After that, the judge may, if he so wishes, give the Public Prosecutor's Office and the defence the opportunity to respond to the victim's statement. The judge can then, if necessary, ask some questions. It is therefore possible to deliver tailor-made work at the hearing, but the time of the right to speak is fixed. This is clear to everyone in the Netherlands: after the actual treatment and before the request of the Public Prosecutor's Office. For the sake of clarity, I would like to say that we support this section. This legislative proposal then extends the circle of spokespersons. With the advent of composite families, there are situations where stepparents or foster brothers and sisters also want to use the right to speak, for example if a family member has been murdered. We agree with the government that the circle can be expanded. An amendment was then adopted unanimously which provides for a general measure of governance to be put forward in both chambers, which determines the privacy sensitive data of the victim from the criminal record. The D.A.'s gonna decide what information that is. One can think of the victim's address, phone number and social security number that reported a crime. The Minister has yet to begin the development of such an AMvB. We are curious to see how this self-justified wish can be implemented in practice without problems, delays and red tape for the criminal case. Victims also have an interest in getting justice done quickly in their case. And that might be at odds with cleaning up the criminal record. Can the Minister explain how the advisory bodies responded to the amendment that was adopted? Is it possible to introduce a sensible approach? I have more questions about this section. Suppose the D.A. pulls some of the victim's data from the file because he thinks that the judge doesn't reasonably need these data to reach a decision. Does the defense know that this data was taken out of the file? Does the state's attorney's office have an information obligation on that? What happens if, for example, it appears that the victim's address is relevant in relation to the scene of the crime? Did the district attorney maybe put the defense at a disadvantage by removing the data? Is this contrary to the principles of equality of arms and a fair trial as referred to in Article 6 of the European Convention on Human Rights? Is there any way for the defense to challenge the D.A.'s decision to abandon the data? What happens if the judge considers that data relevant? Will that be sanctioned, such as the inadmissibility of the Public Prosecutor's Office? Or, if that's considered too strict, what possibilities does the judge have to redeploy this? Can the judge order the recording of the data in the file? If so, on what legal basis can the court order this? Mr. Chairman. My group is therefore concerned about the feasibility of this part of the legislative proposal introduced by amendment. I would like to ask the Minister whether he can promise that he will really take the time for the actual preparation of the AMvB, that he will first have an impact analysis done in practice and that he will let the two chambers know how much the cleaning up of the victim data file will cost. Can the Minister also promise that the introduction will not be at the expense of the existing budget throughout the criminal justice chain? We could also consider bringing this part of the legislative proposal into force later."}, {"speech id": "ParlaMint-NL_2021-04-13-eerstekamer-7.u156", "speech text": "Well, to clarify, and this technical correction can help: they are actually two separate regimes, two separate chapiters. It is already the case that juvenile criminal law applies to juvenile suspects, but this is based on a kind of pedagogical view that it is a good thing that the juvenile suspect is present at the hearing to hear it from the judge and so on. That is independent of these provisions. And there has been a reference that causes confusion, which we would like to get out of again, so we are correcting it in that regard. They're two separate regimes. Finally, on this part. In fact, Mr Otten asked why do you not apply this obligation of appearance more widely, including to suspects who are not attached for the time being? That is also of a practical nature. Experience has shown that in many of these cases the suspects are still in custody, but in cases where this is not the case, it would also be incredibly demanding from all kinds of authorities to force the suspects to be present at the hearing. Then you need to start checking if anyone's willing to come willingly. And if that's not the case, then you have to send all kinds of agencies to track down someone like that and force them to go to court. In other words, that is a lot of hassle and is, in our view, very difficult to implement. Mr. Chairman. 