he instructions for violence. Violation of the violence instruction is punishable. A further distinction is made between cases where there is an infringement of the instruction of violence as a result of a culpable error of judgement or carelessness and cases where an investigative officer intentionally violates the instruction of violence. Mr. Chairman. Practice teaches us that in most cases a policeman or woman has to decide in a split second. A violent use can consist of rolling each other down the street or worse, cases where the service gun must be used. In all cases, the violence used will comply with the definition of acts of violence. One can think of abuse or even manslaughter. What is currently happening in practice is that a police officer who uses violence at first instance is regarded as a suspect, even if after the investigation it appears that this policeman or woman is going free because he or she acted according to the instruction of violence, or that he or she acted out of self-defense. The aim of the legislative proposal before us now is to put an end to this situation in the sense that a police officer is no longer directly regarded as a suspect. A good thing, given the special task of the police. To this end, a separate research framework has been included in the legislative proposal. For example, after the use of force which results in serious physical injury or the use of the firearm, an investigation of the facts carried out by the State's Attorney's Office may be initiated at the request of the Public Prosecutor. It seems clear to me that the truth must be at the forefront of this fact-finding. The outcome of the fact-finding will clarify whether the policeman or woman concerned has used the violence according to the instruction of violence. If this is not the case, a criminal investigation will follow in order to determine whether the new proposed Article 372 Code of Criminal Law has been infringed: violation of the instruction or a service requirement, instead of the investigation focusing on serious abuse or manslaughter. A clear distinction is therefore made between the fact-finding and the regular investigation. The investigation of the facts is aimed at investigating whether the violence has been used according to the instruction of violence, the regular investigation is aimed at whether a criminal offence has been committed. The investigation of the facts therefore always precedes a possible criminal investigation, where in the latter case the policeman or woman concerned is only considered a suspect. Again: a good thing. Mr. Chairman. This law is linked to the instruction of the office, so to speak, the internal disciplinary process. It indicates the lower limit which violence is certainly not proportional. As far as I understand it, in principle, any registration of violence ends up with the head of the sector. The Head of Sector shall deliver an opinion on the professionalism of the use of violence. This opinion and the underlying documents then go to the Commission on Violence, which also gives an opinion. On the basis of these opinions, the police chief decides whether the use of violence was professional or not. It looks at both the legality of Article 7 of the Police Act and the instruction of the office as well as at craftsmanship. If, in the opinion of the Chief of Police, there is reason to do so, he shall inform the Prosecutor as soon as possible. The Public Prosecutor then decides whether an investigation of the facts is to be initiated under Article 511a Criminal Procedure. It seems to me that the procedure is sufficiently secure in this way. The cases discussed above may lead to an incident coming into line with criminal law after the investigation of the facts. But also a citizen's declaration can ensure that the prosecutor decides to investigate the facts. Is it true that this fact-finding will then be carried out by the state police, the VIC or by another department not involved in the incident? If so, what are the criteria for choosing one or the other route? I'd like a response from the Minister. Mr. Chairman. I will conclude with three questions to the Minister. Firstly, what happens if an investigative officer uses disproportionate force as a result of a culpable error of assessment by the management echelon? What does this mean for the investigating officer in question, and what are the consequences for the echelon in question? My second question concerns a commitment made to three times by the Minister in the Lower House that the notification form should not serve as evidence in a possible criminal proceedings. How does the Minister intend to honour this commitment? Could the Minister, for example, incorporate the commitment into the instruction? Finally, I would like to know from the Minister whether it is true that investigation of criminal investigations or investigation of facts can be used in the course of instruction. If so, could the Minister specify that? Mr. Chairman. So much for my first term. Thank you."}, {"speech id": "ParlaMint-NL_2021-04-22-tweedekamer-5.u82", "speech text": "If people are going through that, it's horrible. If as a child you experience that your parent falls away at some point, for whatever reason I have also experienced it in my own life, that is terrible. But we need to be careful here. In this case, if certain skills were to be taken into account in first aid but there are more to be mentioned than would be taught in education and not as a hard obligation to be included in the curriculum, it could not be so, and that is actually what you indirectly say that the education, where the politics is the client, would then be the culprit of. That does not seem to me to be a fair or fruitful way of talking about this issue. Because if so, all swimming lessons must be required immediately. And if you want to do self-defense, you should, so to speak, include that in education, because then everyone, young and