 importance to no direct or indirect vaccination coercion. At the same time, it is this cabinet that is frustrating within Europe when it comes to providing free testing. It seems so logical. The government introduces a test obligation, so the government pays for the test. But the Netherlands is therefore annoyed. This cabinet will allow ordinary families to pay hundreds of euros extra to be able to go on holiday, while the vaccines are free. This leads to indirect vaccination. Does the Prime Minister recognize that? Mr. Chairman. Our freedom is in danger. Forum for Democracy would prefer the cabinet to give up on this miserable plan, but if those corona passports do come, will the Prime Minister stop being obstructed? Will the Prime Minister undertake to issue travel certificates after performing a free test? And is the Prime Minister prepared to argue within the EU for a tough end date for the corona passport regime? This shouldn't be the new normal thing. Mr. Chairman. More worrying developments are taking place in the world. Israel's under attack. With Iran's support, Hamas is firing thousands of missiles at the Israeli civilian population. It's only because of Iron Dome that not many Israeli civilian deaths have occurred. I have therefore listened with amazement to the negative way in which some colleagues have spoken about Israel in the past period. They are stuck in their own victim-badder narrative, as if Israel did not have the right to defend itself and as if Dutch interference, let alone Dutch sanctions, would resolve the conflict in Israel. It's time for a sense of reality. It is not in the Dutch interest to play schoolmaster against Israel and Saint Nicholas against the Palestinians. It is in the Dutch interest to trade where that strengthens us and it is in the Dutch interest not to lecture like-minded countries, but to support them when they are under fire. The Prime Minister should therefore not agree with unilateral EU statements that wrong Israel's