ce of words, which makes it possible for the Netherlands to play that role. That makes us quite unique in the world. We are truly one of the few countries in Europe where both the Palestinians and the Israelis turn to do business. I think there are a number of issues to be dealt with here, and I will end with my brief introduction, which has to be resolved. For example, the Netherlands is thinking about how to solve the issue of Palestinian division. In the end, you want the PA to be able to go back to Gaza. We think that is very important. We also think it is very important that Israel strengthens Abbas's position. What is happening now, of course, weakens the position of the Palestinian administration on the West Bank. A third issue relates to the reconstruction of Gaza. Again, there is the importance of predictability and speed, for example when deciding on the passage of building materials and other goods. I also think that the distinction between Israel and the settlements remains very strict in all aspects: not only in Dutch-Israeli cooperation, but also in the cooperation between Europe and Israel and, of course, in the Dutch efforts to bring Israelis and Palestinians together on both sides of the green line. With the trilateral groups I was talking about, we will also continue to try to solve these structural problems in the fields of water, energy and trade. The European Union also relies heavily on the Netherlands to continue with this. Mr. Chairman. Okay, here's a little introduction. Then I'll come to the questions. The first is, of course, about the Palestinian families in Sheikh Jarrah. We are very concerned about this expulsion, which I have just mentioned in general terms. We believe that this kind of unilateral action is contrary to international law. They also undermine the possibility of a two-state solution and can lead to further escalation. We think it is a good thing that there is a court ruling to postpone this threat of expulsion. We urge Is