e conditional on disarmament of Hamas. In the long term, it is simply necessary for the Palestinian Authority to return to Gaza. That is what the efforts are aimed at, but that is, of course, for the longer term. Yes, it is true that the right of veto is an excellent part of the European spectrum of instruments, but in areas of common foreign and security policy, in particular sanctions and human rights declarations, the cabinet is in favour of lifting that veto. At present, however, there is still insufficient support for this. There was a very specific question about Turkish Hamas terrorists. Mr De Roon said they had a passport. The notice on this can not be confirmed on its own. If members of terrorist organisations already had a Turkish passport, it would not make it any easier to enter the Schengen area, because visa granting at the border is by default subject to a check, including through the Schengen Information System. Then I come to the terrible story about the bombing of the mediators in Gaza. We are, of course, very concerned about this. It is crucial that the press remains safe and can report. Israel states that Hamas also used the tower. By the way, this is denied by the AP, the media organisation. We do not have any independent information on this. We believe that, after all that is happening now, there should be wide-ranging independent research on both sides, both Hamas and Israel. I say this specifically in response to questions from Mr Van der Lee, but also from others. We do not therefore have any independent information to determine whether that attack was proportionate. Then there is the question of whether we want to support Israel at EU level. As I said, the Netherlands supports Israel's right to self-defense, but within the limits of international law, including the issue of proportionality. A powerful country such as Israel, which has one of the strongest military forces in the world, naturally has a special responsibility. I've just said a few things about that. Of course Israel has the right to self-defense in that context. Then there was the question: how do we look at the next steps if a cease-fire were to come? We believe that the idea put forward on this subject, namely a suspension of the association agreement, is not sensible. This is the political and legal basis for cooperation between the EU and Israel and is therefore an important instrument for relations. We, as the Netherlands and as the European Union, are engaged in an intensive dialogue with Israel, but also with the Palestinian side. That is precisely what is needed in order to be able to raise all the issues that arise in this case. Then a question was asked about the message that Israel would have two schools in sight in Gaza. The people in the schools and surroundings were indeed warned. The bombings, according to our information, have finally stopped. Then several questions were asked about the term \"apartheid.\" As I have already said, the cabinet is concerned about the general situation in the occupied Palestinian territories. The report by Human Rights Watch shows the impact of the occupation on the lives of Palestinians and the unequal status between the inhabitants of the settlements and the Palestinians in that area. The cabinet is reluctant to use qualifications such as \"apartheid\" until such qualification has been established by an international court. Then there was also the specific question of how we look at the Karabulut motion on a concrete step-by-step plan. Are we working on that? Yes, of course. Stef Blok, the Foreign Minister, asked the High Representative and the Special Representative, Mr Koopmans, our former colleague here yesterday; 'your former colleague', from this role, I should say, in fact, to propose concrete measures, with concrete lessons for reconstruction, but also with concrete steps in response to the events that preceded the violence, such as the already mentioned threatening home expulsions, 