xt you are sitting in your room in Webex with colleagues and that against the backdrop of another crisis that would come next, that of the childcare allowance, where it was of course also the question of whether there was any real contact. Is there any way to have real contact in this digital world? Despite the crisis we were in, opportunities have nevertheless been found, including in a state-wide sense, to bring service to the citizens. Although it is not the subject of this debate, I can announce that we have taken a number of measures and have made plans to work towards the future, based on the lessons we have learned, with the working environment for the future, with hybrid works, in whatever form. I am really convinced that we must take advantage of the lessons that have happened to us all and not just turn to business as usual and fall back into our old behavior. I think we could really get the good things out of this structuralally. Looking at the way we have all done this and the role of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs in it, I note that we have been able to do this mainly with conviction and good cooperation. I do not have a Compliance Act, which has, of course, been quoted a lot today, on the basis of which I was able to do so, but there was just a broad conviction that we were all going to do it. In that conversation, in that consultation, we're still sitting. I am pleased with that, and I believe in it, because in the end, not only the experience of the departments, but also of the people who have done that work mean that we are going to do things differently and better. Then I'll get to the second block. That is ICT and information security. This is a difficult subject, which has been the subject of attention for many years, including from the Court of Auditors. This has to do with the fact that we are in a situation where on the one hand we are becoming increasingly dependent - and, on the other hand, corona has made that clear - of the fact that we need to digitally and at the same time the threats have increased. We're not in a static state. Every day, we have to keep our lines of defence in order, keep them in order, and with all kinds of government organisations, implementation organisations, co-governments, because, of course, criminals and other actors seek out the weaknesses and thus question the legitimacy and integrity of these systems. This is something we need to avoid, because citizens and businesses need to be able to trust that information and services are actually in the right hands of the public authorities and that all kinds of data are not compromised. When it comes to information security, we were also confronted with the Citrix crisis at that time. I welcome the fact that the Court of Auditors has made a positive comment on this. The Court of Auditors has, of course, the legal task of indicating where things are not going well, where there are shortcomings and where any objections are raised. Here, I think we have been able to show that what we had prepared also worked in practice. We learned from that again, so we can only do better. I thought it was a good example where you can see how, from the direction of steering, that steering is not based on legislation other than the Compatibility Act, which has worked well together several parts of the Empire, in particular the CIO Empire and the NCTV, to ensure that we could act on that very quickly. Nor did it cause any major problems. So that calls for attention all the time. In doing so, I do not have the expectation and illusion that all the shortcomings in this area will be resolved next year, without being able to complete next year's annual report, because there will always be new challenges. That is an additional need to give it from the Empire's side more than ever before the attention it deserves. Of course, your Chamber has already acted on this by setting up its own committee for digitisation. Then I come to sustainability. About this g