opt is supported by the General Court. Then there is a question from Mr Sneller. Referring to the fact that a Digital Affairs Committee was set up, he reminded me of a discussion that had previously been held in this Chamber about the usefulness or necessity of a state inspection digitisation. That was the Middendorp motion at the time. Mr Sneller wondered: \"There was no national inspection. What are the alternatives? Has the mind stopped or is that going on?\" We did have that discussion. We didn't choose a state inspection digitization. In the debate we have had on this subject, I indicated that the basis for that inspection is a very different one from the Compatability Act under which the National Finance Inspectorate operates, where financial management is concerned. We have chosen to control the provision of information to the State Service with a number of measures and to strengthen that provision of information. This means that the Decision CIO-system of the National Service 2021 has now entered into force. This enables us to steer and strengthen the management of the IV and ICT domains. We do this by, among other things, positioning the CIO at the board table. That may not seem very important, but that is an important element, because it makes an immediate contribution from the CIO at the heart of the decision-making process. In addition, the CISO, the new function we created, will also be more strongly positioned under the CIO. The cooperation between all the departmental CIOs in that CIO council should ensure that these experiences and knowledge in the departments get a place in the heart of business operations. We also do this with the quality framework for departmental information plans. That'll give you more unity. You do that in a natural way. You're gonna keep all that from being formally imposed right away. In this discussion, agreements are made on how the departments will work together. There is therefore a form of convergence which leads to more uniformity. That is not wrong in itself, because of course we are talking about one government. It would be weird if every department did it their way. But you do feel that there is such a thing as ministerial responsibility. That's gotta come together. That CIO Council and the ministerial responsibility laid down in the Constitution should not ultimately clash. We have also discussed this on several occasions in the cabinet. This is a line that is worn widely. For insight into the state of ICT in the government we have created a dashboard. We have said of this in the first instance: it is good to add projects that are currently in progress. Mr Sneller himself was one of those who said: \"We should also include that management and maintenance, which may not be a part that gets all the attention in the beginning. This is perhaps at least as important; it involves a lot of costs.\" I have already promised you that we will have that operational at the beginning of 2022. I still keep that promise. The supervisory role of the ICT Examination Bureau, which has been established, I would like to remind you that for all those who are new to the Chamber of Representatives on the basis of the Elias Committee, a permanent advisory body is being transformed at this time. In addition to the tasks already carried out by BIT, this involves advising on maintenance and management activities. It will also play a more active role in knowledge transfer and new additional forms of advice. For example, you should think of official organisations, but it could also be in the direction of the Chamber. I expect to be able to consult the draft law on the establishment of this permanent advisory body within two weeks. So that's on schedule on its own. I would like to thank Mr Eerdmans for his compliments on the speed of the changeover. I just said something about that. I'm referring to the other work in the government. It's just... it's just... it's just... it's There is a whole palette of exa