antee 100% safety? I believe that we should make the most of this, that we should do everything in our power to offer this safe environment for children. That is what we must do: at home, at school, anywhere in the society where they are. That is also the approach I take to this issue, but also the way in which I will, from my administrative responsibility on behalf of the cabinet, address a number of very specific questions that have been raised. Mr. Chairman. Which brings me to the report. That report is solid. It is the school itself that asked for an investigation when the article of the NRC came out with the personal experiences of students; some of you also referred to it. I appreciate the school doing that. The inspection has started immediately, in accordance with the legal bases that are in place. The inspection doesn't just work out a little bit in the wild, just to put it down. No, the inspection will have a clear mission, which we have secured by law and regulation. In particular, Article 15 of the Education Supervision Act provides them with legal bases for carrying out such research. They've gone to work. I'll come back to the years before. You could say that, at the time the investigation was started, this did go by the book and the way we recorded it with each other. The inspection is conducting its independent investigation. I repeat, independent investigation. The inspection has produced a report on this matter and has spoken with many interested parties. In the end, the inspection based on these interviews has prepared a report containing recovery orders, as is the case with such investigations, if necessary. It sets out very concretely the shortcomings of this school. The school itself has also put its own hands into this. The school has indicated that many things may go well at that school, including in terms of quality and safety. A lot of students feel safe. But the next thing should be central, because this can never be an excuse to do your j