at did not take place until 2020. Then we'll have more in our hands, I guess, to get there faster too. That is only one side of the matter, because of course it is not just a question of reporting a school. I shall come back later to the fact that I believe that much more is needed and can also be done to speed up the picking up of signals about abuses, and to have a climate in a school that can also be discussed more quickly. At times when you don't feel safe, it's also very difficult to open your mouth to say something about something you experience as unpleasant. We have a responsibility for this too, but I will come back to the third block in a few moments, about the faster picking up of signals. Mr. Chairman. The report has been independently established. I think it would be very bad if we were going to take things out, criticize that report in a daylight that it wouldn't be right. This is the work of the inspection. That is what we asked for from the inspection. It even has a legal basis. On that basis, we must now act simply. The inspection is not a party that when something happens in a school as a kind of referee and says: it is right or it is not or you name it, how you see that in mind when you think of a case like this or perhaps others. The inspection looks at the implementation of the adequacy requirements, and that of course has everything to do with the Education Supervision Act, how it went, how the school set it up and how it was secured so that those things that we ask of a school also take place. On that basis, the report is also built up. Once again, I am pleased to stress this, and I would also like to congratulate the school on the fact that, after the judge had spoken, we have just started to work, and so now, in view of the children, we are also in the process of carrying out the recovery assignments. Mr. Chairman. Specific questions have also been asked about a section of the report, namely how to deal with the coulance regime. That has als