d contraction in the economy was the result of unprecedented budget deficits and rising debt as a result of unprecedented measures. All these shitty measures were necessary, but let's just be honest, it was a very difficult period for everyone. The second story is fortunately a much more optimistic story. This is about a country with enormous resilience and adaptability. We started working at home, zooming, kids were taking digital classes, we were having digital drinks, and we were doing messages for each other. Entrepreneurs continued to fight hard and put their last savings into their business. Like the owner of a bookstore not far from here where I often come. In December she had spent her last savings on Christmas lighting to cheer the store up in the hope of making up for some of the losses at Christmas to hear a week later that the Netherlands had to go back into lockdown. Fortunately, she and all those entrepreneurs were able to count on emergency support. Well spent money preventing many bankruptcies and allowing the economy to make a flying start after corona. The economy is growing again, and how! After a free fall, the economy rises again. Budget deficits are falling and for the first time in a long time there have been more vacancies than the unemployed. Worldwide, our country is being watched with admiration. How do these Dutch people do that? One of the successes is our modern economy. We have many different companies and are not dependent on one sector. Our economy is driven by knowledge, which you can't deactivate with a lockdown. And we're at the forefront of digitalization, for example, which allowed us to work through lockdowns, get kids lessons and keep seeing our family. But I have to be honest, too. We are in danger of falling behind on a number of things. That makes us vulnerable, and we must not let that happen. In the Millions note, the cabinet takes a few important first steps. First of all, security and investment in tackling organised cr