ed. I will come back to the European Union and its distribution in Europe. The Netherlands and the other European countries depend on the United States. Fortunately, the United States has been integrated into NATO. It is a cooperation in the alliance of North American and European countries that is capable of defending us, defending us in Europe. The United States accounts for 70% of NATO capacity. This costs them 3.5% of their gross domestic product per year. The defence expenditure of the European countries is far behind that. That is, of course, a threat to the alliance. That is why the NATO countries agreed a standard of not 3.5%, but 2%. In 2014, they agreed to grow there in Wales in ten years. Our percentage is 1.5%. If we don't do something in the next few years, we'll fall below 1.4% in the next few years. Compliance with the agreement we made in 2014 to reach 2% in 2024 would cost the Netherlands more than 5 billion a year. If we do not want to get out of hand in Europe and reach the average of the European NATO countries, it would cost us some 4 billion extra per year. But that doesn't mean we're here yet. If we have done so and we are all in Europe at 2% and are somewhat more in balance with the United States, then we must realise that the United States believes that Europe must first and foremost take care of its own defence. This requires an effective European defence society, which is still insufficient. In the meantime, America's defence attention is increasingly drawn to China. China is the second economy of the world, has the largest navy in the world and is rapidly developing the land and air force. They are also rapidly producing nuclear weapons. China is also relevant to the European defence, which I will come up with later, but first about Russia. We experience this threat from Russia every day: in the air and at sea; in the corridor of the Baltic countries, Belarus and Ukraine, but also to the south of Europe. Russia uses hybrid warfare, for example by making great use of disinformation to disrupt democracies. Where European countries in the Sahel region are committed to stability and security, Russia is doing exactly the opposite. That threat we are facing is also and increasingly a cyber threat and also a threat in space. Businesses, knowledge institutions and public authorities in Western countries face cyber attacks from Russia and China on a daily and large scale. The purpose of these cyber attacks is to steal information and disrupt stability in our area. Where our physical defence is still credible thanks to NATO and the United States, our cyber defence is not yet, in my opinion, and that is a great concern. I can tell you that in the six, almost seven weeks I've been back on the DOD, I've been working on that cyber threat almost every day. How can we resist them as well as possible? The same goes for our defense for what's in space; trying to resist as best we can. In space, we have set up Western satellite systems for communication and observation, but they are vulnerable to competing satellite systems set up by Russia and China. One is intended to disrupt our satellite systems and the other is about the possibility of firing satellites that they are not on. That is also a threat, far from our bed, but therefore no less real. The defence organisation is also needed every day in the Netherlands. Corona showed it to me, too. If there's a pandemic, then defense is of great value. We need to be able to respond to this at certain times by the civil authorities. This also applies to the Netherlands when there is natural violence, such as in Limburg, but also in Haiti and Albania. Then we are also there to join in on an international scale. What can we, as a government, as a parliament, expect from our armed forces, our defence organisation? Firstly, that is what we have put in our Constitution: the defence of the European territory of the Netherlands and of the Dutch countries and public bodies in the Caribbean. The protection and promotion of the international legal order and stability is the second point in the Constitution. And the third is to support the civilian authorities whenever necessary. Secondly, we can expect our armed forces to ensure that we fulfil our international obligations, particularly in the NATO context, towards the United States. I say it quite frankly, and I have already written it to the Chamber: the defence organisation cannot now meet these legitimate expectations. The organisation is vulnerable because material readiness is below 50% and employability is too low. There is insufficient investment in staff, in renewal, in sustainability of housing, in practicability. There is also insufficient investment in operational support, in stocks, in conservation and in IT. That is the situation at the moment. And I'm not talking about investing more in cyber and space, as I just mentioned. Defense needs to recover. As Van Wijngaarden said, defence must come out of the blue and then it must be renewed. And one can't do without the other. Everything that needs to be done is, of course, directly linked to the financial resources, with the deficit of 4 or 5 billion a year. It is just how you want to see it; the European average or NATO-2%. The expectations we, the government and the parliament, have of our armed forces, have never been lowered. I also think that lowering those expectations is not a real option. In those years, the DOD tried to keep all the balls in the air and fill one hole with another. There is no \"no\" in the Defense Department, so if something is expected of us, we try to get that to the left or right with some sticking and cutting as well as possible. I don't think it's going to be like this anymore. I think that if our people are asked to do their dangerous work, they deserve to be well trained and trained, to have access to the equipment, equipment, armament, support and information they need and to be well rewarded. Mr Pre