ndemic with within certain limits, within bandwidths, persistently recurring likely seasonal recovery. That's kind of what it's all about. The WHO has just indicated that it is too early to really equate covid with influenza in this respect. RIVM did the same. It gives a slightly different picture of illness. If we're going to figure out where we're going with these five scenarios, we're going to have to line out scenario 1 of full dampening right now. It won't be. It may well be that we're about to come up with such an endemic scenario. Especially if we have variants that, such as now an omikron, protect vaccinations and boosters from which a previous infection also protects against and which are less sickening as a net result, then we can come to such an endemic situation. But it's still too early to tell if we're really coming to that. It may also be that at some point there is a new variant that spreads just as fast or faster than the omikron and yet is more sickening again. We just can't predict that right now. Occasionally there are signals of the potential emergence of such a virus. You know that's monitored all the time. That's what people turn up and look at right away. So far, the following variants remain small again, indicating less rapid spread than with omikron. In other words, we're looking at those scenarios. We're taking them too, but it's too soon to say: this will be it. We've been thinking for a long time: it's going to die out, especially with vaccination. Then we thought, \"It's gonna be a flu-plus.\" But it's really too early to really say that. Then there was a question from Mr Van der Staaij about immunity. He asked if it would give more room for young people. Immunity after an infection also works through in the final decrease in the number of infections. So this is also included in models. In the long term, extra space will indeed be created. In addition, an infection can also be used in a corona pass and you do not need to be quarantined after a recent infection. On the question, \"does that give you more room?\" So the answer is yes. Mrs. Tielen asked about the toolbox. She asked what the possible measures are and what it's proven to work. As you know, we have used many different measures over the last two years, with the aim, among other things, of reducing the number of infections, keeping sight and keeping care accessible. What works in an infectious disease is to reduce the number of contacts or to make those contacts as safe as possible. I always say: the chance of getting infected is the number of contacts times the chance of getting infected with a particular contact. That then depends on many factors, which are partly influenced by you. In the meantime, we have also learned a little bit about how people actually deal with measures and what their behavior is. We consider this behavioral component and the wide impact of the measures on social vitality and accessibility of care. We have already done that, but we have to do much more in the future, as has just been discussed. I will come back to that later on. Mrs Tielen also asked about the protocols, the field labs and the co-responsibility of sectors to open up. The results of these pilots, of those field labs, have largely become part of the current measures. Think of making a distinction between placed and unplaced, separating groups, deploying and validating the corona tickets and capacity restrictions. These have also been included in their discussions in the last week by colleagues, including those of EZK, SZW and legal matters. It is also included in various protocols and measures for a wide range of sectors. As the Prime Minister has already said, they have actually indicated: simply give us responsibility and let us help set things up in such a way that we can all open as safely as possible. The same applies to colleagues, but also to myself. I am really talking to a very broad group of sectors, in the form of a sounding board group, to see how we can move towards a good, effective and perhaps, hopefully, more predictable use of measures in the long term. Then Mr Van Haga asked how many infections are prevented by closing at 10 p.m. instead of midnight. It has also just been mentioned that the effect of an evening closure decreases as contacts go through later. Ultimately, it depends on the number of contacts and on the duration and intensity. With a later closure we also take a risk of an increase in the number of infections. I have just mentioned that the OMT and the RIVM were initially on the 5:00 hour line, with an exit to 8:00 p.m., subject to strict conditions. For reasons already mentioned, we finally decided to close at 10 p.m. That is a significant step forward. Then I come to a question from Mrs Tielen about scientific knowledge and models. Her question was whether these models are sufficiently explainable. This is an important point, which is very much addressed. That also affects the subject we have just discussed. We pay great attention to communicating as easily as possible on these topics, in communication about measures, about risks, about the impact and importance of vaccination, about quarantine, about tests and so on. There are also a lot of videos, visuals and hotplates used, along with Steffie modules. I've just had a moment to explain what Steffie modules are. You know it all, but I didn't know it. Many materials are also tested in advance through soundboard groups. So this is the explanation. You can't simplify the models on their own. Sometimes a model is the case: the more parameters you can put in it, the more fine tuned is the result that you will eventually get. But that is, of course, a moving insight based on a model. You have to put the new data in there over and over again, as I mentioned myself. But a lot of attention to that, because it's really important. There was another question from Mrs Tielen. It's also about communicating. Are the press conferences and t