 there is no rape, incest, danger to the mother's life or serious deviation in the unborn child. Unborn life must be protected as much as possible, precisely because it is so incredibly vulnerable and cannot defend itself in any way; not only by parents but also by society. The tragedy of abortion must therefore be avoided and discouraged as far as possible from society as far as FVD is concerned. A legal period of reflection is a measure that aims precisely at this. However, with the present legislative proposal, the initiators aim to abolish the statutory period of five days for abortion. The explanatory memorandum refers first of all to the autonomy and right of self-determination of women. Autonomy and self-determination are also very important core values for FVD. But to what extent are they substantially under pressure because of this period of reflection of only five days? There are legally all kinds of time-limits. It has already been mentioned, among others, by Mrs Palland and Mr Stoffer. For example, the legal reflection period when buying houses is three days. Are buyers affected by this compulsory period of reflection in their autonomy and self-determination? Should this kind of reflection period not also be abolished, as far as the proposers are concerned, with a profession or individual autonomy and self-determination? And what do the proposers of the countless ways in which the State today tries to subtly adjust individual choice behavior to \"nudgen\" as it is now popularly called, for example, by obliging frightening pictures on packets of cigarettes, taxing sugar and alcohol, or by requiring workers to pay a pension? Quite specifically: why is D66 a five-day reflection period for an abortion paternalistic, but is it okay if the State assumes that every Dutchman has no objection to organ donation, unless otherwise indicated? In short, the reference to autonomy and self-determination in the explanatory memorandum to the legislative proposal is not very credible to us. In addition, the initiators argue that the period of reflection is considered uncomfortable by the parents. Understandable, but isn't this the right thing to do? It is literally a decision of life and death, which is incredibly far-reaching and irreversible. Such a decision should not be taken lightly. A legal period of reflection serves to ensure this. That it is annoying for the parents, that may be, but it is not only necessary, but even appropriate as far as we are concerned. Just as grief when a loved one dies is part of life as far as we are concerned, and is not something undesirable. How many parents regret their choice over time, perhaps because they remain unwanted childless at a later stage of their lives? Mrs. Van der Plas just said the same thing. Do the proposers have any idea? This feeling of guilt is, of course, not only a huge taboo, which will make it difficult to measure, but will keep up with them for the rest of their lives, rather than the five-day reflection period that this proposal is about. I would like to give four quotes from parents who have been remorseful of their decision. The first quote: \"I'm happy, really. But deep down, I haven't forgiven myself for my abortion. Afterwards, it turned out to be my only chance at a child. I've managed quite well to push that feeling into the background. But sometimes, when someone from my area is pregnant, or when I see my girlfriend's son, who is now as old as my son or daughter would have been, it hurts a lot.\" The second quote: \"It's now a year and a half later and there's not a moment when I don't think about the child that was never born.\" The third quote: \"After the surgery in the clinic, I was nauseous for a few days. Now I've been sick for eight years when I see an ad somewhere with a happy baby. Then my stomach turns around and I whisper in my mind an'sorry' to the baby that should never be born.\" The last quote: \"Every day I think about my baby. I'm so sorry. So terribly sorry. But I don't know if I'm sorry about the abortion itself or how it turned out. For me, this has really been done to me and I had no other choice at the time.\" Have the proposers realised that more than two thirds of abortion doctors, gynecologists, nurses, social workers and psychologists are largely positive about the period of reflection, because it prevents impulsive decisions? And do they know that a poll among 400 women with an abortion experience showed that 71% found the period of reflection useful? In addition, recent research by DirectResearch shows that a large majority of Dutch people support the mandatory period of reflection. Finally, Mr Stoffer also said: is not every life saved in this way sufficient reason for a five-day period of reflection? However, what we have noticed above all is that the most important consideration for us in the explanatory memorandum to the legislative proposal remains completely unnamed. That consideration is that an unborn life that has the potential to become a fully-fledged human being, just like all of us here in this Chamber, is killed prematurely and knowingly. It is a young, defenseless and early life, which moreover has no voice and cannot defend itself in any way. It is a life that deserves much more protection than a five-day period of reflection. It will be clear that FVD is very critical of abortion. Apart from the known exceptions, as far as we are concerned, abortion is, in principle, undesirable. I repeat the exceptions: abortion after rape or incest, death risk to the mother or serious birth defects in the child. As far as FVD is concerned, the period of reflection is therefore maintained. Except, again, abortion after rape or incest, danger of life to the mother or a serious birth defect of the child. In addition, as is customary in some states in the US, we consider it desirable to have a mandatory ultrasound in an abortion that is not covered by the aforementioned exceptions, starting from ten weeks. Finally. As far as we are concerned, the current 24-week abortion period is far too wide. An embryo can be viable outside the womb at the current state of the art from 19 weeks onwards. We will come up with an initiative proposal which will ensure by law that the maximum abortion period must always be shorter than the number of weeks from when a baby can be viable outside the womb. So that's not 24 weeks, it's 18 weeks. We have already reached out to the SGP on this issue and may hope to be able to send this proposal to the Chamber together with other parties in the near future. I'm closing up, Mr. Chairman. This is the last paragraph. In short, for FVD, any abortion is a tragedy. This is what we, as a society, should want to avoid, discourage and limit as much as possible. As far as we are concerned, the current legislation on abortion, which allows abortion for up to 24 weeks, is far too broad. This initiative proposal makes it a little easier to proceed to an abortion by abolishing the mandatory five-day period of reflection. So we will vote against this bill. Thank you, Mr. Chairman."}, {"speech id": "ParlaMint-NL_2022-02-03-tweedekamer-12.u237", "speech text": "I can try to serve it in all kinds of ways, but I really have to refer to my previous answer. I have a vague suspicion that we will come across this misunderstanding again in another debate. Mr. Chairman. Mrs Piri rightly pointed out the following. Arms supplies are always sensitive. We're willing to look into it. It's about defensive weapons. She said, \"How are we supposed to read that?\" I tried to indicate that in the letter. There too, I have simply wanted to be transparent. There are weapons that are clearly defensive. There are also weapons that are clearly offensive. But of course there are a lot of weapons that can be used for both purposes. So you can't always rule out the use of an offensive weapon that gives you primary defense. But let's be honest. Are we now concerned about a larg