us at all, seems less sickening, but that effect is smaller than with vaccination or the previously experienced infection and thus the immune status. That's a good thing. At the same time, we are dealing with very high contagion numbers, which fortunately now go down. That's why there's a lot of people falling out everywhere. You have seen the images: failure and modified timetables of the NS, a modified timetable of the KLM, hospitals and healthcare partners who have problems with it. And we have a situation where the WHO continues to say by the RIVM, by the Scientific Council for Government Policy, by the Academy: beware, we are still not in a stable situation. You have just used the term \"endemic\" and \"endemic\" a number of times in the debate. If we accept and define endemicly as a stable situation where you may or may not have a constant pattern of contamination with a certain compliance, then we are not there. It may be that we haven't been there for a while. If you look at the different scenarios of the WRR, for example, a palette is sketched. The first scenario was: completely extinct and disappearance of the pandemic. In the meantime, we have to note that the chances of getting there soon are not great, not even after vaccination. We're not getting there. Another variant, completely on the other side of the spectrum, is: continuous wave on wave of a seriously sickening new variant, where a previous infection and vaccination does not protect against. That is still not excluded, but we do not seem to be getting anywhere with that either at the moment. And variants in between are more or less sickening new variants, each time with a revival and hopefully in a setting where it eventually becomes a fairly normal flu or cold virus. We must realise that, even in the case of flu, large numbers of people become ill every year. Especially among the vulnerable in society, there are large numbers of deaths every year. We have incorporated that as completely normal a