 2050, which is clear. The previous cabinet has stated that it is not a question of \"growth\" or \"shrink\" but of guaranteeing the quality of public interests. That's the lead. The coalition agreement that this cabinet received in January also clearly sets ambitions for these frameworks in terms of sustainability and viability, but also in terms of network quality. We've got the Aeronautics Note. This will be further developed in the context of the implementation agenda. That will be a tighter story, given the provisions of the new coalition agreement in which the cabinet I am planning to implement in 2022 to clarify what we call \"security and perspective for aviation'. Security and perspective for the quality of the environment as well as for the interests of the residents, the environment and the nuisance they face. And there is also the importance of having good connections, good network quality, with abroad. This is what the cabinet is shaping this year. It's not gonna be New Year's Eve. In the course of the coming months, the cabinet will decide on this. We are also working on the framework for network quality for the implementation of this network quality. This is also based on the quality of the connections for our country and not on quantity. So that's all that's ever better. The sustainability and quality of life frameworks have also been defined in part and are further defined. In the end, it is up to the aviation sector to operate within these frameworks with a business model that can be profitable. These are many things that apply primarily to airports, but also, of course, to airlines. Mr Crone asked about this framework for network quality and whether Schiphol and KLM would cooperate. We want to take that thoroughly and properly. The framework is now being prepared. That's going to the Chamber this year. We are now in the first phase of development, to give it a good, solid foundation. We do that internally within the government. We are now about at the stage in which we also start the consultation of the corresponding stakeholders, including of course Schiphol and KLM. Eventually, as a government, we make the decisions. Minister Kaag said a moment ago about the business model, but specifically about what that will mean for KLM in the future in the context of the Aviation Note. Mr Crone asked for this: a new business model that is economically profitable and meets environmental requirements. First, the finding that the review of KLM's business model is not part of the aid package agreed in 2020. However, the conditions set out in the support package aim to structurally improve the competitiveness of KLM, including the conditions of network quality, viability and sustainability. Our government guidance on that business model is, as it were, indirectly through the frameworks we set out through the Aviation Note and the concrete measures that are still in line with the coalition agreement. The business model itself is therefore primarily KLM's. But then it comes: in the current and future circumstances KLM can be expected to review its business model in accordance with current circumstances and expectations, such as the environment and climate, where necessary, and adjust its strategy. In the previous report, the state agent made a comment on this: I want to look more closely at how KLM is shaping its business model, its earning model, towards the future. He suggested, among other things, that KLM was in financial trouble in 2020, just like all airlines in the world, because of the consequences of the pandemic, but that at the same time you can learn how to give a little more flexibility to your future earning model. I will not immediately say that you will be able to withstand such a pandemic, but you can think better about the flexibility that goes with it in your business model. The same applies to the flexibility in recovery after the corona pandemic, the question of whether you can have more flexibility in the expectations of the business segment versus other categories of travelers, and of course the flexibility to move constantly and preferably lead the way in terms of the sustainability of aviation. I was talking about network quality, but also about that other aspect of sustainability, the quality of the environment and the reduction of aviation nuisance. Several members of your Chamber, Mr Vendrik, Mrs Prast, Mr Crone, asked how the intentions of Air France-KLM and KLM themselves fit in with the wider need for sustainability and how do we see this in relation to climate change? As mentioned above, we not only want to maintain a good connection, a good network quality at Schiphol Airport, where KLM is of course an important player as the largest user of Schiphol Airport. Through the stock issue we contribute to this through the maintenance of a good information position, but that is sufficiently explained. At the same time, we think it is important that attention should be paid to reducing the negative effects of aviation on people, the environment and nature. As a cabinet, therefore, we are also committed to making the entire aviation sector more sustainable. This will ultimately mean more and more for the largest airline operating in the Netherlands now and in the future. Mrs. Prast already referred to the route there. Then why do you want that through shareholdership if there are other instruments for it? Of course, she's right about that. There are many other instruments. I'll get right on that. In the end, however, it is also important that we not only want the instruments. Of course, we also want the largest airline in the Netherlands to take up its responsibility to proactively implement it in a leading role as much as possible and as soon as possible. Then there is the whole policy on sustainability. The 2019 Climate Agreement contains only a few rules on aviation. The starting point of the Climate Agreement and of all the parties with whom we agreed as a cabinet in 2019 is that the sustainability of aviation and the reduction of CO2 emissions requires an international approach. This approach is international, because aviation is global. It is therefore preferable to do so through global agreements, for example in the context of ICAO, the international aviation organisation. At the same time, in the Netherlands too, the ambition was to see if we could go a step further. Internationally, I referred to ICAO, but of course the European Union makes a number of proposals in the Fit-for-55 programme to reduce CO2 emissions from aviation. These months are also being discussed in the European Union on the incorporation of renewable fuels, but also, for example, on the phasing-out of free allowances in the ETS system, which should include aviation within the ETS in the foreseeable future. This is a very good incentive to ensure that the sector is challenged to the maximum to reduce CO2 emissions. When the Climate Agreement was agreed, there was also national initiative for the Sustainable Aviation Table. That has also led to an agreement. If you take that agreement from 2019, you can see that this agreement is full of ambitions and that almost all the parties involved in aviation in the Netherlands participated in it. In the end, however, it is a roadmap of how the Netherlands can take a leading role in this. For example, the first concrete objective is to integrate 14% of renewable fuels by 2030. Meanwhile, it is also a whole road map of how the aviation sector as a whole in the Netherlands wants to make an effort to get there, knowing that this is, of course, one of the biggest and perhaps most complex transitions in that whole climate issue. There's no such thing as a big jet on hydrogen engines. However, there is a lot of work being done to develop it. So this is not a development that you get introduced from one day to the next. In fact, we have indicated that we want to have a leading position as the Netherlands, but we have very few international control options. If you want to remove a lock for the reason that it is not sustainable, then there is another airline. We don't have any control tools to say that someone else can't have that lock. Nevertheless, from that national agreement of the Sustainable Aviation Table, we have a number of additional national instruments. We have also included these instruments in the coalition agreement. Not only do we have a higher incorporation target than the European Union imagines, but we also intend to set a CO2 ceiling for airports. This cabinet has also taken the initiative for additional noise-insulating measures in homes around Schiphol and for further anti-inhibiting measures. This cabinet also announced its intention to increase the flight tax. It is also committed to a kerosene load in Europe. These are all matters that we have first of all come up with nationally. The state aid conditions package for KLM in 2020 may also be good to remember. That package is also, in fact, a kind of defense brought about by the government. In 2020, the fear was that if your national airline is in such financial difficulties, the commitment to remain part of the national sustainability agenda will go down before you know it. This was therefore also reason to include KLM's commitment to those sustainability conditions, including the incorporation of 14% renewable fuel by 2020. The state agent has pointed out that the KLM has committed itself to the 2030 targets, but that, if one wants to see if KLM is really on the right track, there should also be some sort of growth plan, on the basis of which it becomes clear what KLM expects to have achieved at a number of moments between now and 2030. That's what he reported in the report early this year. That is why Mrs Kaag and I had reason to discuss this with the supervisory board and with the KLM board. We said, \"Give us that plan.\" That wasn't right, but at the same time we also discussed that at the beginning of this year with the board of Air France-KLM, i.e. at holding level, in Paris. I think this is a very concrete example in which your shareholdership also emerges. In the recent consultations Mrs Kaag referred to this shortly before the announcement of the issue, we had discussions on behalf of the Dutch State with the board in Paris. It was also said that the importance and need of a good monitoring plan were seen. At that time, there was also the undertaking from the holding company to ensure that such a monitoring plan from KLM would be drawn up in the foreseeable future. I also think that this is a very concrete example of the operation of the shareholdership, also as a second shareholder. The same applies to the fleet renewal that Mrs Kaag mentioned. At the beginning of this year KLM announced a large-scale fleet renewal, with the Boeing 737 coming out and the much more economical and quiet Airbus 320 coming in. That is also one of the subjects that we discussed directly at the level with the board in Paris, the CEO there, and also with the Dutch board member, who has also worked for this. Those were the comments on sustainability. It is true that we can enforce everything through laws and regulations, although sometimes things are slow and the ambitions of the Netherlands often extend beyond, for example, what is now on a number of topics in Fit for 55. Do you also want to make sure that these conditions, once they are there, are quickly arrested by the Dutch airline, then it will help to sit at KLM's table in all possible ways."}, {"speech id": "ParlaMint-NL_2022-06-02-tweedekamer-18.u301", "speech text": "Mr President, I think it is a good discussion. The essence of this afternoon also comes down to this. Of course, I have to advise my group and I read the motion in such a way that what the service does, the NCTV does not. You said it yourself, Minister. That self-defense investigation isn't intelligence. So what the services do, the NCTV doesn't. We all 