ry disappointed at the outcome of the motion. The only thing the previous cabinet has done is to create an A4 with a decision-making tree for officials, so that it is clear to officials when they can make use of Article 2.27. In fact, there is only one question: is there sufficient time for parliamentary authorisation? If no, use Article 2.27. It's in the A4's. Mr. Chairman. This can't be happening. I should try this at home. I want a new car tomorrow. You know what, I'm gonna buy it right away and at home I'm gonna say, \"Sorry, honey, there wasn't time for familial authorization.\" I'm afraid I'll be sleeping in that car from now on. Article 2.27 was invoked 40 times in 2020 and reached 59 times in 2021. This would mean that the importance of the Empire was at stake five times a month. And the counter goes on. The exception article has been used 24 times this year. When you look at the motivation in the incidental supplementary budgets of this exceptional article I've been studying them all over the past few weeks, you're actually reading something interesting. Then you see that over time a different argument is increasingly being used, namely that there is an urgent nature of the payments. The policy must be implemented quickly. But that's not what Article 2.27 is about at all. It is not about speed of policy but about whether the importance of the Empire is at stake, which means that speed is necessary. In a crisis situation, of course, it may be true, but Article 2.27 is also increasingly being used outside crisis situations. If we look at 2022 alone, this year, we see expenditure related to ventilation measures in school buildings, a rolling lease at Foreign Affairs or a European hydrogen project. That will all be very good spending, but they are no reason to put Parliament out of play. In addition, Article 2.27 states that the States General should have been informed, which led to the Prime Minister's remark last year that the cabinet might have had to put a stamp on a note more often. Technically, he was right, but that was obviously not in the spirit of the law. And right here, it's pinching. When it comes to sound fiscal policies, the Compatibility Act now leaves too much room for interpretation to the cabinet. It needs framing. Or, more flatterly, we want our ATM card back. I therefore propose that Article 2.27 be supplemented by the condition that the States-General should not only be informed, but that the States-General should also be informed. This puts the Chamber in a position to judge whether the importance of the Empire is actually at stake and it also forces the Chamber to take up a position. Because in all honesty and that is what I am responsible for, we have not asked for any additional supplementary budgets on this point, of course. I will table a motion for a resolution on this point in my second term. In addition, I will take the initiative with Mr Sneller, as chairman of the Committee on National Expenditure, to draw up a protocol on how we wish to be informed, also taking into account a crisis situation in which we must act quickly, because that is, of course, ultimately for the Chamber."}, {"speech id": "ParlaMint-NL_2022-06-09-tweedekamer-8.u230", "speech text": "I still have a question about the funds. I will not ask what the Minister is going to say next week, but I would like to go back to the Growth Fund. That too was not a very nice procedure. It came all of a sudden. Things have already been set in motion. In the end, in constructive negotiations, we had to force a separate institutional law. This institutional law has been introduced and then it is decided very quickly to pull out an important part of the Growth Fund. My question is, in fact, the following. The defense was all the time: you set something apart; you don't touch it, because you have a purpose for it. This objective will be secured for a multiannual period with a certain amount. But in practical terms, I see that Cabinets, the