t Chamber.' At the time, there was also a wide-ranging debate on the mandatory period of reflection. PSP Senator Joop Vogt was critical. Compared to the practice now established, however, we are clearly declining qualitatively, he said. The five-day reflection period can in some cases be very burdensome, discriminatory for women, or at least seen by a very large number of women. At the time, the law was passed in your Chamber with 38 votes in favour and 37 votes against. Today, we are happy to discuss this law with your Chamber and the mandatory period of reflection. On this side, I would also like to wish Mrs Gerkens and our co-initiator both the best of luck to Mr Van Wijngaard and to thank all the spokesmen for their questions and the attention they have given to the legislative proposal, including in the written round. We will, of course, do our best to answer all the questions as best we can. There are three of us here without Mr Van Wijngaarden. We will all take part in the answer, so let me start by giving you the railway book. Mrs Ellemeet answers all the questions relating to the professionalism of care. In doing so, she also raises the questions as to what exactly this law will mean for the procedure to be followed and for the doctor's job. Mrs Kuik will answer the questions that have been asked about the social basis, the role of the man, who has also been on the subject, the legal aspects. She will include other reflection periods mentioned in the debate, both in the medical field and in private law, and she will answer the questions about the implementation of the legislative amendment and the evaluation of the law. I begin by answering the questions about the cause and the intended outcome of our proposed legislative amendment, the balance in the law between protecting unborn life and caring for women in an emergency situation, the culture related to aborting pregnancy, and the answer to questions about scientific justification. If we have to say once or twice that another initiator has to answer the question, then excuse in advance. Mr. Chairman. I should like to begin by answering the question on the basis of this initiative. In particular, Mr Van Dijk specifically asked for this in his speech. At the time of entry into force in 1984, to which I referred, the legislator considered that creating the balance between caring for a woman and the protection of unborn life required the mandatory minimum period of five days of reflection. These five days would ensure that the woman would make an informed choice. In fact, it is implied that without those five days the choice would not be careful or considered in sufficient cases. This assumption appears to be incorrect, as it has repeatedly proved since the adoption of the law 38 years ago that a fixed mandatory period of at least five days is not necessary to make an informed choice. That is what the 2005 and 2020 legal assessments show, because they both advise to abolish that fixed period of reflection. Mr De Vries of the Otten Group pointed out in his speech that in 2012 the World Health Organisation had the same opinion to all countries with a mandatory period of reflection, namely to remove this period of reflection. Therefore, the mandatory period of reflection does not achieve the intended objective. In addition, we see that it does lead to adverse effects. The mandatory period of reflection causes negative effects on the emotional well-being of women and causes psychological complaints. It also mentioned something that could not be foreseen in 1984. Due to the mandatory period of reflection, there are also limits at stake, which sometimes require a more severe procedure in order to break down pregnancy. As a result, women are restricted in their treatment options. This in turn leads to a greater risk of complications and therefore less good care for women. On the other hand, professional assistance and good support for women in need do contribute to making an informed choice. Therefore, the initiators aim to change the fixed period of reflection to the flexible period of reflection. It recognizes that every situation is different. We believe this contributes to tailor-made care. The woman determines in conversation and with the help of doctors how much time she needs to reach a decision. With this change of law, there is therefore plenty of room for a shorter or longer reflection period. The period of reflection therefore remains, albeit not legally, five days. That is the essence of what we are arguing. Mr Van Gurp asked whether we had also considered removing the period of reflection entirely from the law. We have tried to stay very close to the evaluations and, moreover, to what the Council of State recommended. For example, the first review of the law states that there should be such a reflection period as is necessary in order to reach an informed decision in the circumstances. The evaluations show that this is also the wish of the professional field. We therefore believe that a flexible period of reflection is more appropriate than a complete abolition of that period of reflection. Mr. Chairman. Questions have been asked about what this says about our culture. For example, Mr Van Dijk said that this proposal would facilitate the termination of pregnancy. They asked what impact this has on culture. This is more of a normalization of pregnancy termination, if I may paraphrase him like that. We like to give that reflection. The proposers consider that a pregnancy break-up cannot be seen as an isolated element, because it concerns the whole of good sexual and reproductive health care. Sexual education and accessible contraception together contribute to preventing unwanted pregnancy. That is also an important consideration which Mrs Vos and Mr Dittrich pointed out. Looking at the Netherlands, we see that the figures for pregnancy breaks have been stable for years. Compared to countries with comparable levels of registration, these figures are relatively low. In this respect, therefore, we do not believe that there is a trend towards normalization of pregnancy break-up. In fact, in this respect, we agree with what Mr Kox said. There still seems to be a taboo in the Netherlands to talk about a situation in which a woman has had to abort pregnancy. Rather, we believe that it will benefit the provision of care if there is no longer a taboo and if there is more open discussion about it. But the fact that there is a taboo does say something about the fact that there has been no standardisation in our view. Mr Van Gurp asked whether the initiators considered that termination of pregnancy should be part of criminal law. We have, of course, talked about this. We note that this issue is of a very different order from the law as we have now presented it. The idea of putting the legislation on abortion into a completely different legal framework is, of course, something other than the substantive change that we are proposing today. We defend the law here on behalf of the House of Representatives. So, in that sense, I can imagine that the subject will certainly come back, but what we personally consider to be a little less important today. What we are saying is part of the reflection, I say to Mr Van Dijk, is the following. It is wrongly said that converting a mandatory period of reflection into a flexible period of reflection leads to the idea that many thresholds are being removed and that the termination of pregnancy becomes much easier. We have the idea that the qualitative guarantees, as they are listed in Article 5 of the law and have all been incorporated in almost 200 pages of guidelines of the Dutch Association for Obstetrie and Gynaecology and the Dutch Society of Abortion Doctors, aim for a very large part to ensure that there is a careful consideration on the basis of the decision to break down pregnancy. That's a very difficult decision. The compulsory period of reflection also has a very little influence on the decision, which is why we do not think it will remove the threshold, but will improve care."}, {"speech id": "ParlaMint-NL_2022-06-15-tweedekamer-8.u223", "speech text": "Agreed. But a letter has already been promised by the cabinet in the debate with the financial spokesmen. Let me take a look at your colleague, Mr Van der Lee. That letter's already in the making. I can't tell if it's there tomorrow. We want, of course, to take the latest developments with us. But it's already been promised. Mr Dassen asked about the green golden rule. What are we doing to maintain forward-looking investment in these times? Mr Dassen may remember our letter with our own commitment through the non-paper of the Stability and Growth Pact. That letter contains a paragraph on possible funds or the green golden rules. A defense rule comes up as well. There's going to be a social investment rule. In many countries, this debate is going in all directions. So we said in the letter of 4 March that we are reluctant to look at it and want to ensure that countries make choices in a normal, orderly fiscal policy with investments, reforms and credible debt disposal. The sustainability of debt is a major issue. A golden rule, in any form whatsoever........................................................................................................................................................................ In this period that is really undesirable. We also have the 'Fit for 55' programme and REPowerEU. There are many other paths and investment opportunities for many EU countries. Mr Klaver asked how the Netherlands fulfilled its obligations on the African continent. Are we gonna take extra steps over there? That's a very fair question. I believe that you were the only one who spoke to Mrs Simons about the consequences of hunger, displacement and displacement as a result of this crisis. It will be much larger outside Europe. That's already playing. The Ministe