66 but also on behalf of the Animal Party. So let's see how that works out. Mr. Chairman. I shall begin with the new Article 17, the right to a fair trial. We believe it is important that the right to a fair trial is now enshrined in the text of the Constitution. One of the reasons is that the law as enshrined in the Constitution is more extensive than the scope of Article 6 of the European Convention on Human Rights, which already applies in the Netherlands. This concerns civil law, administrative law and criminal law, but also, for example, foreign law. In determining the merits of an action brought, one is entitled to a fair trial, but also in determining rights and obligations. This makes the new Constitutional Article 17 important. So that must not be or become a wash nose. During the previous treatment at first instance, the child care allowance scandal has been discussed on several occasions. We all know that public authorities such as the Tax Administration have acted in an incredibly wrong way, and those seeking justice in the Netherlands have suffered. The judges, who are there to speak independently and impartially about disputes, have also attracted the fine. In other debates, this scandal has been dealt with in detail. The various actors have promised to get better. There are many facets to the right to a fair trial. In legal practice, there appear to be bottlenecks which deserve our attention as co-legislator. I would like to ask the government a number of questions about this. They are aspects of, for example, the criminal proceedings that do not normally lead to major headlines, but which are of great importance for people in the Netherlands, for example when they are suing against the government. It is common for the State to make a mistake in a specific case, to conclude a settlement agreement with the deputy and to grant a sum of damages. In future, if the State pays compensation to citizens in the context of the new administrative culture, is the government prepared to waive the clause that the content of the scheme should not be communicated to the outside world? I ask this because people learn from mistakes and how to deal with them. Then society must be made a part of it. So I'd like a response from the Minister. What lawyers regularly encounter is that the Public Prosecutor's Office actively contacts the Dutch media prior to and during a criminal case. That is to inform the public, but sometimes also to influence the public. When it comes to the right to a fair trial, you might ask: why does the D.A. actually do that? How does the Minister view this? Should there not be a code of conduct for the Public Prosecutor, as is the case for lawyers, for example? If the Public Prosecutor thinks he should look up the media, shouldn't it inform the defense in good time in the context of equality of arms? How does the Minister feel about that? If material is seized in criminal proceedings, such as computers, accounting, etc., then the Public Prosecutor's Office may refuse access to the defence and also refuse to provide copies, while this is really relevant for the proper assessment of the case. Is it not important, in the context of a fair trial, for the defence to have the same information as the Public Prosecutor's Office based on in good time? Should the Code of Criminal Procedure be amended for this purpose? So far, the Public Prosecutor's Office has determined what does and what doesn't end up in the criminal record. In other countries, such as the United States, this right is enshrined in the law within the framework of equality of arms. Mr. Chairman. Unfortunately, it appears that the prosecution does not include exculpatory witnesses' statements in the file and does not inform the defence of its existence. The question is therefore: what is the value of a judicial investigation if exculpatory facts are kept out of the file? Because a prosecutor belongs to the judiciary. He serves the truth finding. Attorneys regularly complain that exculpatory evidence is not presented by the police and the Public Prosecutor's Office. How does the Minister respond to that? What can be done about this, do we want to implement the right to a fair trial properly? I would remind you that yesterday there was a big article in the Volkskrant about the Deventer murder case, which also mentioned that certain detectives had not included certain facts about a scent test with dogs in the file and had received a stand for it. This proves that things like this can occur in all kinds of cases. Sometimes it also happens that really incorrect information is recorded in a report, for example that a witness wanted to make a statement or did not mention any fact, while later it turns out that the witness explicitly stated the opposite. Is the Minister prepared to communicate clearly to the Public Prosecutor and the police that this is contrary to the basic rules of truth finding and organising a fair trial? Then something else. The Legal Assistance Board is formally governed by the Ministry of Justice and Security. If someone has to sue against the State, for example the Public Prosecutor's Office, it does not feel right for the Council to decide whether or not someone is eligible for funded legal aid. Is the Minister prepared to examine whether it is possible that, when the government is a trial party, an organisation more remote from the JenV Ministry will consider whether funded legal aid can be allocated? A Dutchman who is arrested abroad for a criminal offence committed abroad is, in principle, not entitled to funded legal assistance under the law, because the Dutch interest would be lacking. But sometimes the witnesses to that foreign case take place in the Netherlands precisely because the witnesses are Dutch and live here. The foreign lawyer of the Dutchman must then employ a Dutch lawyer for legal aid. And that Dutch lawyer sometimes has to spend hours preparing the case and attending witnesses' interviews with the Dutch judge-supervisor in relevant cases. Will the Legal Aid Council continue to say: 'It is a foreign matter, there is a lawyer, the law does not provide for this situation'? But if the Dutch suspect is unable to pay a Dutch lawyer in detention abroad, he will find himself at a huge disadvantage. My question to the Minister is whether, in the context of a fair trial, there should be a hardness clause in the regulation as regards the provision concerning the Dutch interest. Strangely enough, in a case in which the Legal Assistance Council says that the Dutch interest is lacking, the costs of legal aid are reimbursed by Dutch witnesses who in the Netherlands are required to make a statement to the court commissioner in that foreign criminal case. Does it happen more often that the D.A. does reimburse witnesses' legal aid, but not the defendant's? What's that based on? What does the Minister actually think of that? Mr. Chairman. Already in the time of Minister of Foreign Affairs Hans van Mierlo has been agreed with the House of Representatives that every Dutchman who is in pre-trial custody abroad, or is serving his sentence, should be visited periodically by a Dutch embassy employee. The right to a fair trial also extends to Dutch in foreign detention, especially when a request to transfer the execution of the sentence can be made. The Netherlands has a duty of care. This should not become dependent on the media attention that a lawyer in the Netherlands can generate in order to enforce such a visit abroad. My question to the Minister is: are all Dutch prisoners visited in foreign detention, as agreed with Parliament? Are there countries with white spots? Where can this improve? Mr. Chairman. The constitutional right to a fair trial will only come to life if the Dutch State behaves fairly and fairly. It is therefore important to include this right in the Constitution. I therefore hope that legal practice will show that improvements will result from inclusion in the Constitution. I am therefore looking forward with interest to the Minister's reply, although I am aware that the portfolios of her colleagues at the JenV ministry are also affected by this. Mr. Chairman. Then there is the constitutional change on a electoral college elected by non-residents for the election of the First Chamber. I lived abroad for 12 years, in New York and Berlin. When something happened in the Netherlands, people always came after me. This applies to all Dutch people abroad. Then they immediately asked: what is going on in the Netherlands? If you live abroad as a Dutchman, you are, as it were, an ambassador of your own country on an interhuman level. Then it is strange that as a Dutchman from abroad you can participate in the Lower House elections, or in the elections to the European Parliament, but not in the election of the First Chamber, just because you do not live in a Dutch province or in the Caribbean Netherlands. The bill we're discussing today will fix it. Of course, it is important to know what the implementing law will look like and what choices the House of Representatives will make about, for example, the voting value. Can the Dutch be compared abroad with those in a province? How exactly does that work? We believe that this debate should not take place now, but when the implementing law comes our way. The proposal was submitted to the House of Representatives in April, as I recall. It would be very nice if the new system could be applied at the Provincial State elections in March 2023, but it would have to be accepted by the House of Representatives quickly and then discussed here again. Is that feasible in terms of time? How does the Minister view this? Mr. Chairman. Then there is the constitutional change on the inclusion of the general provision in the Constitution. In 2012, the First Chamber adopted the motion of Hans Engels of D66 on that general provision in the Constitution. It expresses the fact that the Netherlands is a democratic constitutional state. We believe it is important that this general provision precedes Article 1 of the Constitution and, as it were, sets out the framework from which the Constitution, a living document, should be read. I ask the Minister what other changes to the Constitution are actually planned for the government. How is the Constitution brought to the attention of education? The Constitution will soon exist for 175 years. What attention is the government going to pay to this? Article 120 of the Constitution states that the courts may not review the laws against the Constitution. The Remkes State Committee proposes constitutional review. The coalition agreement also writes about this. When can we then receive in the First Chamber the main note of the Minister with variants of that constitutional review? It is a subject that the First Chamber is very close to. We would like to discuss this further with the Minister. Mr. Chairman. Finally, the change in the Constitution of the provision on the immunity of letter, telephone and telegraph secrecy. We welcome the fact that the wording in the new text is made technologically neutral, but it remains difficult to find out when citizens are protected against the government on the basis of Article 13 or on the basis of the privacy article 10. That has to do with the content of the messages or the transport of those messages. My final question to the Minister is: can the Minister explain the delineation of these articles for the history of law? 'Cause it's kind of complicated to figure that out. Thank you."}, {"speech id": "ParlaMint-NL_2022-06-30-tweedekamer-5.u39", "speech text": "Mr Van Baarle uses words like \"defense line,\" but I have nothing to defend. This is just the point of view. This is how we look at it. For example, if trafficking in human beings would mainly take place from Germany to the Netherlands, then it is important that someone working at customs should perhaps do an extra ch