riffs, which have enough critical questions to ask, but also about removing so-called non-tariff barriers to trade as far as possible and the liberalisation of services and, crucially, investment. In doing so, CETA is a very neo-liberal treaty. I would like to say once again, President-in-Office of the Council, which is based on the philosophy of: the more liberalisation, the more market, the more large jobs for large companies, the better. But, Mr. Chairman, we know better by now. CETA places multinationals above people and does so again by legally anchoring the interests of investors and giving exclusive protection by the so-called Investment Court System, the ICS. This is a parallel legal system created specifically for multinationals. This viphof for multinationals is the worst element of CETA and more than sufficient reason to be very opposed to it. That is why, in the rest of my speech, I shall first address our objections to the ICS in detail. Next, I will deal in turn with the undemocratic way in which CETA harmonises laws and regulations and how CETA is committed to undesirable deregulation and liberalisation. Finally, I will mention how bad CETA is for the climate, for animal welfare and for farmers. Mr. Chairman. The ICS is therefore a court that is only accessible to companies, and in practice it is the large companies. They may sue governments if they consider that they have been mistreated by the relevant authorities, even if that had happened at the level of local authorities, such as municipalities and provinces. They can then file billions of claims. Conversely, governments cannot charge them, either trade unions, environmental organisations or other civil parties. One element that has not yet emerged in the discussion is that the ICS only reviews CETA and its investment protection. An investor who goes to the ICS excludes any review of national laws or treaties, such as human rights treaties or the Paris Climate Convention. Therefore, the ICS-arbiters to be appointed by CETA do not need... No, that does not allow them to balance wider interests, taking into account, for example, the rights of workers or the climate objectives. Those who have devised this must consider the interests of multinationals and their shareholders to be very high. But let us be clear: CETA is largely conceived by and for multinationals and increasing their power and profits. Article 112, first paragraph, of the Constitution provides that the judicial authority is to be entrusted with the trial of disputes concerning civil rights and claims. In spite of this, CETA thus gives direct access to a special court, only for investors, outside our judiciary. Isn't this at least a bad relationship with our own democratic rule of law? I'd like a response from the Minister. According to 20 professors and other lawyers, CETA is even contrary to our Constitution. The Minister will undoubtedly see it differently, but the question to her is how many examples she knows, apart from the ICS and the so-called bilateral \"Investor-State Dispute Settlement\" mechanisms, of international courts to which private parties have direct access without having to go to court first. Is there such a court for workers or for disadvantaged citizens? Or are only multinationals entitled to such privileges? It also affects our legal order and our sovereignty. I'd like a response from the Minister. And the question to the fellow senators is: can a treaty which is seen by so many experts as contrary to our Constitution be accepted? Even if you judge that conflict differently, you have to think three times before you approve a bill that raises such questions about its legality. After all, here is also a core task for us as the First Chamber. The fact that Canadian multinationals, as well as American via Canadian subsidiaries, and their shareholders have direct access to the ICS, so without having to exhaust the national legal process first, makes the road to claims even shorter. In addition, these claims at such a special investor court are expected to be much higher than in our national legal system. I mentioned a similar system in an interruption earlier. That is the Energy Charter, which a majority of the House of Representatives, including D66, is now quite rightly seeking to get rid of, precisely because of the ISDS system. Through this similar treaty, the German energy giants RWE and Uniper have now demanded EUR 2.4 billion for the closure of coal power plants. If that is granted, that money must be coughed up by the taxpayer. And this as a result of democratic policy choices made by the Netherlands. Madness! That is absolutely unacceptable. Does the Minister consider such claims against his own cabinet policy to be normal? I'd like a response. Now, in answering the many questions from this Chamber, the Minister repeatedly points out that there is no reason to expect an increase in claims from Canada based on CETA, but there is no logic here."}, {"speech id": "ParlaMint-NL_2022-07-11-eerstekamer-3.u616", "speech text": "Mr. Chairman. I ended my speech in the first term by saying that this treaty is good for everything that stands for the economy of \"more, more and more\" and that it is very bad for the much-needed transition to a fair, social and sustainable world. I have to say that the Minister's answers merely confirmed that sentence. It does dispute that the objective of CETA is to maximize trade liberalisation, but at the same time it mentions figures that are entirely about the increased volume of trade, more exports and more imports. The Minister also reported very proudly that the EU and the Netherlands have a trade surplus. This means that we have apparently been very successful in exporting to Canada, including the export of more meat. Because exports of meat to Canada have doubled. And if there is one thing we really need to work on, it is meat consumption anyway, if we really want to put the fight against climate cha